Whakamārama: Te whakahaerehanga o ngā mahi whakahaere.
Scope Note: Business acumen and management.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tikanga nehe o te mahi hī ika, kua whakamahia e ngā whānau, e ngā hapū, e ngā iwi o ngā moana o te waitai, o te wai māori hoki.
Scope Note: Customary and subsistence fishing of marine and freshwater environments by local whānau, hapū or iwi.
Whakamārama: Ka kohi kai i te wai māori, me te wai tai.
Scope Note: Gathering of food from fresh and/or saltwater.
Scope Note: Land based food gathering.
Whakamārama: He rākau waimeha. He rahirahi, he matahua ngā rau. He itiiti, he kaho he maha ngā pua. He porouri ngā hua. He māhoe, he kaikōmako ngā rākau hika i te ahi.
Scope Note: A common tree with thin oval leaves, producing many small cream flowers and purple berries. The soft wood was used with kaikōmako for making fires. Melicytus ramiflorus.
Whakamārama: He momo māhoe, he roroa atu, he whāiti iho ngā rau, he hāura kōwhai ngā pua.
Scope Note: A tree resembling the māhoe but with longer and narrower leaves and yellow brown flowers. Melicytus lanceolatus.
Whakamārama: Ko te atua o te ahi.
Scope Note: The goddess of fire. In some southern tribes, Mahuika is referred to as a male.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā ringaringa o te wharepuni ngā maihi e pōwhiri atu ki ngā manuhiri, arā kei mua i te wharepuni ēnei, i runga i te mahau.
Scope Note: The outstretched arms of the meeting house.
Whakamārama: He momo otaota, torotika tonu te tupu, ia tau ka puta. He kāriki hāura ngā pua. He kai te para.
Scope Note: An erect annual terrestrial orchid with an edible tuber and green/brown flowers. Orthoceras strictum.

Whakamārama: He tohu nō te ngākau aroha ka whakapuakina e te tangata, engari, he poroporoaki, he kōrero taumata hoki mō tētahi ika i mōnehu ai, ā, ka pānui atu ki te iwi whānui e pēnei tonu ana ki aua kōrero kua tāngia i te moheni a Mana.

Scope Note: Literally "song of affection for the dead", a written farewell tribute to someone who has passed on, like those seen in the Mana magazine, that usually include a short biography of the deceased person’s life. See also: Pānuitanga mate (Death notices).
Whakamārama: He mauwha itiiti, rite nei ki te mingimingi. Ko ngā rau he ngohengohe, he kakara, hei mahi hinu tīare.
Scope Note: A small shrub with small greenish white flowers, red berries and a soft sweetly scented leaf used for cosmetics. Phebalium nudum.
Whakamārama: He rākau nui nō te wao. Ko ngā rau he rarahi, he kōroaroa, he kāwitiwiti. Ko te tino wahie hei tahu ahi. He matahua te hanga o ngā hua, he kura kita, he kōwhai kita.
Scope Note: A large canopy tree with large spearshaped leaves. The timber was a favourite type of firewood, heavy and hard. The egg shaped fruits are bright red or yellow. Nestegis cunninghamii.
Whakamārama: He momo maire, anō tōna rite ko te maire raunui engari he whāiti ake he paku iho ngā rau.
Scope Note: A large canopy tree with narrow spear shaped leaves and a tapering fruit. Nestegis lanceolata.
Whakamārama: He momo maire, he whāitiiti rawa nei ngā rau.
Scope Note: A type of maire with very narrow leaves. Nestegis montana.
Whakamārama: He rākau tōhihi, he whāiti he mōhinuhinu ngā rau. He kura ngā hua.
Scope Note: A slender tree with glossy narrow leaves and a red fruit. Mida salicifolia.
Whakamārama: He rākau mānihi te kiri engari he mōwhakiwhaki . He tauaroaki te tupu o ngā rau. He mā ngā pua, he rite ki o te akatea. He kura kita ngā hua.
Scope Note: A smooth barked tree with paired opposite leaves and clusters of flowers resembling those of a white rātā. The fruit is bright red. The wood is brittle. Syzygium maire.
Whakamārama: He mauwha rīrapa, he ririki ngā rau, he mā, he rite ki te whetū ngā pua. Kei te taha moana kei nga whenua reporepo e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A shrub with diverging branches, small narrow leaves, and white star-shaped flowers. It grows in salt marshes and boulder beaches. Plagianthus divaricatus.
Whakamārama: Te huinga weu e tipu ana i te ūpoko o te tangata.
Whakamārama: Ko te whare maire te wāhi hei ako i ngā āhuatanga o te mākutu. He patu i te tangata kia mate.
Scope Note: The Māori version of necromancy, casting spells to cause death.
Whakamārama: Te wahine nāna i whakawhānau ai te tamaiti ki te ao, nāna rānei i whakatipu.
Scope Note: Mothers and older female relatives, sometimes thought of as teachers. See also Kuia (Elderly women, Grandmothers).
Whakamārama: He kaponga tino rahi, he mangu te tīwai me ngā tākaka.
Scope Note: A large treefern with a black trunk and blackish fibrous roots. Cyathea medullaris.
Whakamārama: He rākau ririki nō te ngahere. Kei ngā takiwā ki te raki o Kāwhia me Tokomaru e tupu ana. He rite ngā tātārau ki te parirau. He rahirahi ngā rau.
Scope Note: A small tree of forest margins in the regions north of Kāwhia and Tokomaru Bay. The leaves are thin and prominently veined with winged petioles (leaf-stalks). Coprosma arborea.
Whakamārama: Koia te ihi, te wehi i whakaheke mai ai i ngā atua tae atu ki ngā tāngata kia tū hei māngai mō rātou i te ao tūroa nei.

Scope Note: Spiritual authority and power derived from the gods delegated to humans to act on their behalf and in accordance with their revealed will. Use narrower terms where appropriate. See also: Atua (Gods), Tapu and Whakapapa (Genealogy).
Whakamārama: E kore e taea e te hunga mate i te ngoikore engari kia tū pakari ai.
Scope Note: Personal identity and self-awareness. See also Tuakiri (Identity).
Whakamārama: Ka heke haere mai te mana o ngā atua ki roto i ngā ariki, ā, ka whakauru atu ki roto i te tangata e whakarite ana i ngā tikanga atua.
Scope Note: Sacred power of the gods which is given to those persons who conform to sacred ritual and principles. See also: Atua (Gods), Tapu and Whakapapa (Genealogy).
Whakamārama: He mana hei mana tangata.
Scope Note: The right to political independence.

Whakamārama: Mā te wai ka whai oranga tātou nō reira he tino taonga ia mō te whenua me te taiao. Kia āta tiakina e tātou ngā mātāpuna, ngā awaawa, ngā roto, ngā moana katoa mō te oranga o ā tātou uri whakatupuranga.

Scope Note: Expresses the spiritual and historical relationship between peoples and the waters on or bordering their lands, and the moral authority and responsibility to use and safeguard these. Includes the care and preservation of rivers, lakes and oceans for future generations.
Whakamārama: He tāne ta te tāne mahi.
Scope Note: The male element and the position held in society.

Whakamārama: Ko te mana kua whakatau mai ki te tangata nā ōna pūkengatanga hei hiki i te mana o te whānau, o te hapū, o te iwi hoki. Waihoki, he mana tō te tangata i runga ake i ōna kaha ki te whai i te mātauranga, i tētahi tohungatanga hoki.

Scope Note: Authority, influence and support earned through ones personal achievements and ability to lift the mana of the whole group. In addition, it also signifies an individuals ability to develop skills and to gain knowledge in particular areas.
Whakamārama: Ka heke haere mai te mana o ngā ariki ki ngā rangatira, ā, kua haere atu ki te tangata.

Scope Note: Chiefly power or authority that originates from the atua/gods and is handed down through senior male lines from generation to generation. See also: Tapu, Tūpuna (Ancestors) and Whakapapa (Genealogy).
Whakamārama: He wahine ta te wahine mahi.
Scope Note: The female element and the position held in society.
Whakamārama: He mahi whakaritenga, he tikanga, he kaupapa, he ture hoki e pā ana ki te mahi whakahaere o tētahi rōpū kia taea ai te tū.
Scope Note: A set of processes, customs, policies, laws and institutions affecting the way a group is directed, administered or controlled.
Whakamārama: He tikanga hou. Ko ngā whakaaro me ngā kōrero o te tangata, whānau, hapū, iwi ranei.
Scope Note: A contemporary concept of intellectual and cultural property.
Whakamārama: Hei tauira, ka muimui mai a tauiwi ki te taone nūnui o Poneke i te Whanganui-a-Tara, engari kei a Te Ati Awa ngā tikanga o taua wāhi. Nō rātou te whenua.

Scope Note: Customary law relating to the iwi/tribe's connection, ownership rights and role of stewardship to a particular area of land. Used by council bodies to identify the tangata whenua/indigenous people of that particular area.
Whakamārama: He ratonga hei manaaki hei āwhina i te tangata kia whakatau ai i āna taumahatanga, i āna raruraru rānei ka pā atu ki a ia.
Scope Note: Professional assistance and guidance in the resolution of personal difficulties.
Whakamārama: He reo aroha, he atawhai hoki ā te tangata ki tētahi atu.
Scope Note: A term to express love and the concepts of hospitality and mutual obligation.
Whakamārama: He momo whakakai tēnei, mau i te kakau. E ōrite ana tana tinana ki te ngārara engari ko āhua manu tana mahunga.
Scope Note: An adornment usually worn about the neck of an image resembling a reptile with a birdlike head.
Whakamārama: He rākau tupu i roto i ngā repo waitai. Ka toro ngā pakiaka, ā, ka puea ake i rahaki atu.
Scope Note: A distinctive tree with ascending aerial roots, growing on mudflats. Avicennia resinifera.
Whakamārama: He momo haka tēnei engari e kaha ana te riri o te kaihaka.
Scope Note: A type of haka performed with much aggression and anger.
Whakamārama: He huruhuru whenua ririki, tōtoro te tupu, hei whakakakara i ngā hinu panipani.
Scope Note: A small creeping fern used in making scented oils. Probably Hymenophyllum sanguinolentum.
Whakamārama: Ko te awa iti purua o te awa matua.
Scope Note: A term for tributary rivers, streams or brooks, often used as a prefix in placenames.
Whakamārama: He ika kaikiko. He kākonu, he pango, he roa, he pāraharaha pēnei i te tātua te hanga. He roa, he kokoi te kauae.
Scope Note: A slender carnivorous fish with silver and black colouration and a long pointed jaw. Thyrsites atun.
Whakamārama: Ko te māngai e tū kanohi ai ka tohua hei kaikōrero mō te rōpū.
Scope Note: Representatives appointed as speakers of a group. Use for works about representation.
Whakamārama: Hei tauira tukutuku mo ngā whetu, arā ko mangaroa.
Scope Note: The tukutuku/lattice work design resembling the Milky Way.
Whakamārama: He maha ngā peka o tēnei rākau, he porokura ngā kākano.
Scope Note: A much branched small tree with purplish red fruit. Litsea calicaris.
Whakamārama: He aka rīraparapa ngā tātā. Ko ngā rau, he kāriki a roto, he hinatea a waho.
Scope Note: A vine with tangled masses of stems with scattered forked leaflets, green above and grey underneath. Lygodium articulatum.

Whakamārama: He momo whetū i te rangi e kīa ana ko Tuahiwi-nui-a-Rangi, ko Te Ika-a-Māui, ko Te Ika-matua-a-Tangaroa, ko Te Ika-o-te-rangi, ko Te Ikaroa, ko Te Tuahiwi-nui-o-Rangi, ko Te Whenua-o-te-rangi, ko Te Mangoroa, Ko Te Mangoroiata, ko Te Mokoroa-i-ata, ko Te Paeroa-o-Whanui, ko Te Awanui-a-Rangi, ko Te Ika-o-Raki.
Whakamārama: He otaota rite ki te rērēwai. Tipu ai i roto i te wai. He matahua ngā rau, he taupua ētehi, he taupunga ētehi.
Scope Note: A water plant with oblong floating leaves and similar submerged leaves. Potamogeton suboblongus.
Whakamārama: He rākau roa nō te wao. He rite ki te kauri. Kei te rohe o te Tai Tokerau e tupu ana. E mata ana, he rite ngā rau ki o te tōtara. Kia pakari, kua pipiri te noho o ngā rau.

Scope Note: A tall tree resembling the kauri and, like it, found mainly in Northland. The young leaves are sharp pointed and narrow like those of the tōtara but the adult foliage is scale-like. Halocarpus kirkii.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā manu kātoa o Aotearoa.
Scope Note: A general term for all birds.
Whakamārama: Ko te manu he momo taonga tākaro hei tuku ki te rangi, rere haere ai.
Scope Note: Kites of varied shapes and sizes, made from different materials.
Whakamārama: He taonga tākaro i ūhia te hanga o ēnei momo manu ki te hiako mā o te aute.
Scope Note: Bird-like kites, with a frame of mānuka covered with bark cloth made of aute (paper mulberry).
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo manu kei tātahi e noho ana.
Scope Note: Birds of the seashore.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo manu o te aumoana. U ai ki uta ki te paopao.
Scope Note: Birds of the open ocean.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo manu o te ngahere.
Scope Note: Birds of the forests.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā manu kua ngaro i te tirohanga kanohi.
Scope Note: New Zealand birds which are now extinct.
Whakamārama: He manu rerekē, he manu huruhuru pango. He āhua karaka/kōwhai tōna waha, he kōwhai i waha i ōna karu. He āhua parauri te uwha, me he waha parauri.
Scope Note: Turdus merula, a very common introduced bird. The male is glossy black with orange-yellow bill and yellow eye-ring, while the female is dark brown with a brownish bill.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo manu o ngā repo.
Scope Note: Birds living in swamps and marshes.
Whakamārama: He taonga tākaro rite ki te manu te hanga, he whai anga māmā ka uhia ki te raupō, ki te pepa, ki te aha atu.
Scope Note: Bird-like kites with a frame of raupō covered with different materials.
Whakamārama: Ngā momo manu o ngā awa me ngā roto.
Scope Note: Birds of freshwater habitats, rivers, lakes, etc.
Whakamārama: Ko te hunga (tauhou pea) ka whakaeke ki te marae, ki te kāinga, ki whea rānei.
Scope Note: Visitors or guests of the tangata whenua/indigenous people of a place.
Whakamārama: He mauwha tupu noa. He rite ki te kānuka engari he nunui ake ngā pua. He mā, he māwhero rānei ngā pua.
Scope Note: A very common shrub, resembling kānuka/White tea tree, but with larger white or pink flowers. Leptospermum scoparium.
Whakamārama: Ko te Māoritanga ngā tikanga katoa e pā ana ki te iwi Māori.
Scope Note: Māori culture, practices, and beliefs.
Whakamārama: He toetoe rahi, he huruhuru, he ura ngā pūhui pua. He ura anō ngā pata.
Scope Note: A large sedge with a hairy, tasselled flowerhead of a reddish brown colour. The nut is also reddish brown. Gahnia setifolia.
Whakamārama: He whenua, he wāhi hei tipu hua whenua, hua rākau, putiputi rānei.
Scope Note: Use for all kinds of gardens.
Whakamārama: Te wāhi wātea i mua i te whare tupuna hei wāhi tutakinga ai mo te tangata whenua me ōna ope katoa.
Scope Note: The space in front of the meeting house, traditionally enclosed.
Whakamārama: Ko te āhuatanga o ngā taniwha e whao ana ki runga i ngā whakairo.
Scope Note: Mermen or sea creatures of several varieties depicted in carvings.
Whakamārama: Mā te marama e whakatohungia ana te wā mō te tipu kai, mō te kohi kai hoki.
Scope Note: Planting by the moon. Can be used for examples of calendars or for works about calendars.
Whakamārama: Kare e kore he māramatanga kei tua atu i te mātauranga kei roto tonu i te tangata.
Scope Note: The understanding/enlightenment of knowledge.
Whakamārama: He tā moko i te rape.
Scope Note: These tattoos are on the buttock area.
Whakamārama: Te tirohanga o te āhua me te noho o tētahi iwi.
Scope Note: The study of an iwi/tribe's social structure.
Whakamārama: Te whakaritenga ā-ture e mana ai te moe tahi a tētahi tokorua.
Scope Note: A general term covering all types of marriages, including de facto relationships and civil unions.
Scope Note: A protective garment/apron worn by men or women.
Whakamārama: He momo kakahu, arā he arai e mau ana i te tangata e makariri ana i te huka, te hukarere aha rānei.
Scope Note: A type of apron worn as a protective warm garment to ward off the cold, particularly snow, sleet, etc.
Whakamārama: He maro kākaho mo ngā wāhine kohi mātaitai.
Scope Note: An apron made of reeds and worn by women when gathering shellfish.
Whakamārama: He maro mo ngā wāhine hanga i te anga, i ngā raukura aha rānei.
Scope Note: A highly ornamental apron decorated with feathers, shell, etc. and worn by women.
Whakamārama: He maro rau karamū mō te tohunga i ngā wā kawe ritenga mō te riri.
Scope Note: A ceremonial apron made of karamū leaves and worn by a tohunga/priest for ceremonies associated with war.
Whakamārama: He maro he mea whakapaipai ki te hukahuka.
Scope Note: An apron decorated with a fringe.
Whakamārama: He ika rite ki te aua rarahi. Ko ngā pakihau kei ngā taha o te tinana, he tino rarahi. Hei te whakapūhorutanga, ka toro ngā pakihau ka whakatipi.
Scope Note: A fish like a large aua/yellowed-eyed mullet but with very large pectoral fins which it uses to glide upon after leaping clear of the water. Cypselurus lineatus.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo kōhatu hei tārai taonga tapatapahi, pērā i te rehu, i te paretao rānei.
Scope Note: Glassy or siliceous stone such as flint, obsidian or chert, used for making cutting tools.
Scope Note: A type of ritualistic chant.
Whakamārama: He momo māripi, i tāraia ki te paretao, ki te niho mangō rānei.
Scope Note: A saw like weapon made from flakes of obsidian or sharks teeth fitted into a wooden frame.
Whakamārama: He rākau roa, he pākarukaru noa te kiri. He pango ngā hua. E mata ana, he rite ngā rau ki o te miro. Kia pakari kua rite ki te rau tōtara.

Scope Note: A tall tree with bark which flakes off in scales. The fruit is black. The young leaves are spread in a plane like those of miro. The adult leaves are sharper and narrower more like that of tōtara. Prumnopitys taxifolia.

Scope Note: An identified traditional fishing ground used for customary food gathering as defined in the Fisheries (Kaimoana Customary Fishing) Regulations 1998 established under section 186 of the Fisheries Act 1992, for non-commercial or trade purposes. Managed by a committee made up of members authorised by the tāngata whenua of the area who may put bylaws in place to manage non-commercial fishing. Use for works about iwi and hapū fishing activity in Mātaitai areas. See also: Taiapure (Fishing areas (Commercial)).
Whakamārama: He māramatanga i homai e te wāhi ngaro.
Scope Note: The gift of seeing beyond sight.
Whakamārama: He momo whetū e rere ana ki te ao, engari ka pā ki te whenua.
Scope Note: A type of star similar to a comet except that it falls to earth.
Whakamārama: He tuna waimāori. He āhua roa ake te pakihau o te tuarā i tō te puku.
Scope Note: A common freshwater eel with the fin on the back only slightly longer than that on the belly.
Whakamārama: He tohunga tiaki te māra kūmara.
Scope Note: A priest with special functions in connection with overseeing the planting and harvesting of the kūmara crop.
Whakamārama: Kotahi noa iho te matapihi. Koia nei te wini.
Scope Note: The window of the meeting house.
Whakamārama: Ko te pīnga o te wai e rere ai te awa.
Scope Note: Sources of streams and rivers.
Scope Note: Can be used for examples of encyclopedias or for works about encyclopedias.
Whakamārama: Ko te matareo te pūtake ki te ako te whakaako i te reo.
Scope Note: The interface of language, including the learning and teaching of the language.
Whakamārama: Ko Matariki he tohu o te tauhou o te iwi Māori.
Scope Note: The rising of the Matariki constellation signals the beginning of the Māori New Year.
Whakamārama: Momo tikanga pērā i te tikanga a iwi; te tika me te whakatakotoranga tikanga.

Scope Note: A type of custom or plan that is ethically correct, e.g. a tribal tradition. Matatika may be used with another term to convey different ethical systems. For example, to convey "Environmental ethics" apply both "Matatika" and "Taiao".
Whakamārama: Mo te hī ika te matau.
Whakamārama: Ko te mātauranga te puna o ngā mōhiotanga katoa, mai i te tupuranga, te mahinga, me te akoranga.
Scope Note: Theoretical or practical knowledge acquired through education and/or experience.
Scope Note: The study of sociology.
Scope Note: Scientific study of crime.
Whakamārama: Te mahi whakaora i ngā kararehe.
Scope Note: The treatment of diseased or injured animals.
Whakamārama: Te akoranga o te wao.
Scope Note: The scientific study of plants.
Whakamārama: Te akoranga o te āhuatanga o ngā kararehe.
Scope Note: Zoology, the study of the natural history and science of animals.
Whakamārama: He peka matua tēnei o te mātauranga pūtaiao e aro ana ki ngā mea ora o te ao nei.
Scope Note: The scientific study of living organisms.
Whakamārama: Te akoranga a te āhuatanga o te whenua.
Scope Note: Detailed description on maps of natural and artificial features of a town, district, etc.
Whakamārama: Te akoranga o te whakaora tangata mate i te wairangi, pōrangi rānei.
Scope Note: The study and treatment of mental illness.
Whakamārama: Te akoranga matū i ngā oranga, hiko hoki o te Ao.
Scope Note: Science of the elements and compounds and their laws of combination and behaviour under various conditions.
Whakamārama: Te āta tirohia i te noho piritahi o ngā mea ora i te ao.
Scope Note: Study of the relation of organisms to one another and their surrounding environment.
Scope Note: The study of mankind, societies and customs.
Whakamārama: Te akoranga mātauranga o ngā tōrangapū a te kawanatanga.
Scope Note: Study of political activity and systems of government.
Whakamārama: Te tirohanga o tere, o te kaha o te haere o ngā waka ātea.
Scope Note: Science of rocket propulsion.
Whakamārama: Te mātauranga o te reo, me pehea tōna tuāhua aha rānei.
Scope Note: The scientific study of language and its structure.
Whakamārama: Ko te mate he mea kino ka pā ki te tinana, ki te hinengaro rānei.
Scope Note: An affliction affecting the body or mind.
Whakamārama: Ko te nuinga o tēnei momo mate he rite tonu ki te makutu.
Scope Note: A reaction to an event that affects the mental, spiritual and physical well-being of a person, e.g. Rain of the children.
Scope Note: See narrower terms for specific cancers, e.g. cervical cancer, lung cancer
Whakamārama: He mate ā hinengaro, ā tinana, ā wairua hoki.
Scope Note: Mental, physical and/or spiritual illness.
Scope Note: Infectious diseases such as influenza, distemper, typhoid and typhus fever. Use narrower terms if available.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tikanga katoa e pā ana ki te mate o te tangata.
Scope Note: The rites, rituals and ceremonies relating to death.
Whakamārama: He momo pātītī, he whāiti ngā rau, kei ngā puke kirikiri ē tupu ana. Kāore he peka o ngā pūhui.
Scope Note: A medium-sized grass with narrow leaves and a simple spike. It lives on sandhills. Austrofestuca littoralis.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti o te ngahere, he rite ki te tītitipounamu. He hina te poho. Hanga noa ka kitea.
Scope Note: A small forest bird like a tītitipounamu/rifleman, with a grey breast. It is now rare. Xenicus longipes longipes.
Whakamārama: He matuku mā tōna kanohi, he āhua hina ōrangi tōna tinana. He pango ōna ngutu, me tōna tipuaki engari he kōwhai ōna waewae.
Scope Note: A medium-sized heron with a white face and a blueish grey body. The bill is black and the legs are yellow. Ardea novaehollandiae.
Whakamārama: He momo toropapā he whāiti ngā rau, he kōwhai ngā pua.
Scope Note: A narrow-leaved kind of forest shrub with tubular yellow flowers.
Whakamārama: He āhua hina ōrangi ngā huruhuru o tēnei manu o te ākau. He kōwhai ngā ngutu, he āhua kārikikaho ngā waewae. Noho koromeke ai ki te whakamomoka i tāna pārurenga.
Scope Note: A medium-sized heron with greyish blue plumage. The bill is yellow and the legs are yellowish green. It stalks its prey with a crouching gait. Egretta sacra.
Scope Note: The art of using a staff, sharp at both ends.
Scope Note: The art of using a flat-bladed hand-held club.
Scope Note: The art of using a long club similar to a taiaha but tapered to a sharp end.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā āhuatanga katoa e pā ana ki ngā Rākau ā Tū e ngā whawhai ke tā te tikanga a Tūmatauenga.
Scope Note: The martial art that teaches the use of the taiaha and other Māori weapons in combat.
Scope Note: The art of using a long club similar to a pouwhenua but widens to a "tongue" at the end
Scope Note: The art of using a long axe-shaped club.
Whakamārama: He momo atua a Māui.
Whakamārama: Ka mau te hono o te tinana, te wairua hoki i te mauri Māori.

Scope Note: Mauri is the essence or life-force of both animate and inanimate objects. It binds the two parts of body and spirit together. When a living thing dies, its mauri/life-force dies with it but the wairua/spirit lives on.
Whakamārama: Ka whakahē i tētahi āhuatanga e whakaarotia ana kei te hē, ka tohe kia turakina, kia kaua rānei e whakatūria, e whakamanaia.
Scope Note: Declarations of objection made in public to express disagreement or disapproval about an issue.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā otaota rite ki te rākau ririki ururua te tupu.
Whakamārama: He momo Aitanga Pepeke, he rite ki te pihareinga. He roroa ngā waewae o muri, hei tarapekepeke.
Scope Note: A general term for grasshoppers.
Whakamārama: Ko te hunga tōrangapū kua pōtitia ki roto o te Pāremata hei māngai mō te iwi.
Scope Note: Politicians holding seats in Parliament. See also: Kaitōrangapū (Politicians).
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tū, he kōhatu, ahakoa he pounamu te nuinga.
Scope Note: A flat weapon of stone, often of greenstone.
Scope Note: Venus as an evening star.
Whakamārama: He momo wāhi mō te mahi a te Mihinare.
Scope Note: Religious missions or mission stations established for the purposes of missionary work.
Whakamārama: Kei te aumihia te tangata ki te tangata.
Scope Note: Salutation, pay homage, pay compliment, acknowledge.
Scope Note: Informal welcome. Reconnecting those who already know each other rather than a pōwhiri which is the meeting of strangers.
Whakamārama: He tangata ka tukuna ki whenua kē ki te kauhau i te whakapono, e tahuri ai ngā tāngata o reira ki taua whakapono.
Scope Note: Missionaries sent to other countries to carry out religious work for churches, to invite people to accept their faith.
Whakamārama: E pūrei ana te tangata i ngā momo kēmu, momo tākaro rānei mā te mihini ātea.
Scope Note: Use for computer hardware only.
Whakamārama: He mauwha, he rite ki te mānuka engari he ririki, he kārikitea ngā pua. He ririki, he kura ngā hua.
Scope Note: A shrub resembling mānuka but with small greenish white flowers and small red berries.
Whakamārama: He rākau roa, he porotaka te kāmata, he papakiri, he pāraharaha te takoto o ngā rau. He kura, he matahua ngā hua, he tino kai nā te kererū.
Scope Note: A tall tree with a rounded top. The bark is scaly and the leaves are spread in a plane. The fruit is egg shaped and red and the kererū/wood pigeon likes to eat it. Prumnopitys ferruginea.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti nō te ngahere, he pango te māhunga me te tuarā. Tāpua kau ana te āpure mā kei te rae. He mā anō te poho.
Scope Note: A small forest bird with a black head with a prominent white patch on the forehead. The back is black and the breast white. Petroica macrocephala toitoi.
Whakamārama: He manu nunui, rite ki te emu, kua ngaro noa atu i te whenua.
Scope Note: A general term for extinct giant ratite birds resembling the emu.
Whakamārama: Te waitai te wāhi o kiwa, te wai Māori no ngā awa me ngā roto.
Scope Note: Any body of water, for example, sea or lake. Also, the plants that grow in the water.
Whakamārama: He taonga tākaro i herea ai ētahi taura ki tētahi takaore kei runga i tētahi pou.
Scope Note: A type of swing using poles and ropes.
Whakamārama: Ki te moe koe, ka takoto koe, ā, ka kati i ngā whatu, ka whakatā ai tō tinana me tō hinengaro.
Scope Note: Use for works about sleep.
Whakamārama: He roa, he whāiti tēnei ika. He rite ki te ihe engari he koroaroa, he koikoi ngā ngutu.
Scope Note: A slender fish like an ihe/garfish but with both the upper and lower jaw extended to make a sharp beak. Scomberesox saurus.
Whakamārama: He whakaaro, he āhua, he ariā ka whakaaturia ki te hinengaro i te wā e moe ana.
Scope Note: Dreams. See also Matakite (Second sight).
Whakamārama: Ko ngā pūrongo kōrero katoa, tae ana ki ngā pukapuka me ngā hautaka e pā ana ki te ao Māori.
Scope Note: Can be used for all types of periodicals, including magazines and journals, or for works about all types of periodicals.
Whakamārama: He ika itiiti, he rite ki te kupae. He ōrangi te tuarā, he kāriki ngā taha, he kākonu te puku. He mangu ngā kōiraira kei te tuara.
Scope Note: A small fish like the kupae/sprat, with a blue back, green sides and silver belly. There are black spots along the back. Sardinops neopilchardus.
Whakamārama: Te mōhiotanga o ngā tuhituhinga.
Scope Note: The understanding of words. The ability to read and write.
Whakamārama: Te mōhiotanga o ngā kaute me ngā nama.
Scope Note: The understanding of the basic principles of mathematics.
Whakamārama: Ko te koi o te hinengaro o tētahi ki te ako, ki te whakaaro hoki te mōhiotanga.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti nō te ngahere, he rite ki te pōpokotea. He kōwhai kita te māhunga me te poho.
Scope Note: A small bird of the forest with a bright yellow head and breast, otherwise resembling the pōpokotea/whitehead. Mohoua ochrocephala.
Whakamārama: He kararehe, he manu, he aha atu rānei ka puritia e te tangata hei hoa mōna.
Scope Note: Animals, birds, etc kept for companionship, a person's enjoyment or as a household animal.
Whakamārama: E kiia nei, "ko te tau o taku ate". Ko te aroha a tētahi. Ko tētahi engari ēhara ko rāna e piritahi ana.
Scope Note: A cherished or favoured child.
Whakamārama: He kaupapa i hangā ki te raupō, ka whakatere i te wai, hei waka, hei kawe taputapu.
Scope Note: A raft made of raupō/bulrushes, used at the Chatham islands.
Whakamārama: He huruhuru whenua rite ki te kōwaowao engari he whāiti iho ngā rauhuru, he kārikiuri, he kakara.
Scope Note: A fern resembling kōwaowao/a creeping fern, but with narrower, darker, scented fronds. Phymatosorus scandens.
Whakamārama: He moko kauwae noa iho mo te wahine kē.
Scope Note: These are chin tattoos traditionally for women.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā ngārara ririki rite ki te tuatara te hanga, engari he unahi katoa te kiri.
Scope Note: A general term for skinks.
Whakamārama: Te tamaiti a te tama, a te tamāhine, a te irāmutu rānei a tētahi tangata, tētahi ahu tamaiti rānei o te whānau kei taua reanga, kei tētahi reanga rānei o raro iho.
Whakamārama: He mauwha ririki kei ngā whenua rei teitei e tupu ana. He whāiti, he ura ngā rau. Kia whatiia ngā peka ka puta te haunga.

Scope Note: A small shrub of high country peatlands with narrow reddish leaves and a smell of turpentine when the branches are broken. This name is also used for Kirks pine (Halocarpus kirkii). Dracophyllum subulatum.
Whakamārama: He momo waiata tangi ka rongo i te pōuri nui i te rironga o tētahi mea, pērā i te matenga o te tangata e aroha nuitia ana.
Scope Note: Traditional laments, mostly songs of farewell, to express the emotions felt at the loss of a beloved person or object.
Whakamārama: He huruhuru whenua wekuweku, mōhinuhinu. Puta tonu ake ngā manehau i ngā rauhuru.
Scope Note: A tufted shining fern with small plants growing directly on the fronds. Asplenium bulbiferum.
Whakamārama: Hei kai mo te ika i te hī ika.
Scope Note: The bait on fishing hooks.
Whakamārama: He momo tauira, āhua rānei mo te mahi tukutuku.
Scope Note: A type of lattice work pattern.

Whakamārama: Ka murua, ka pārurehia, ka eanga hoki e tētahi mō te hara a tētahi atu. He tikanga tūturu tēnei o mua hei whakahaere, hei whakarite hoki i te hapori kia ea ai ngā hara, ā, ka tohaina anō ngā rawa me ngā taonga ki te whānau.
Scope Note: To plunder, confiscate, take ritual compensation - an effective form of social control, restorative justice and redistribution of wealth among relatives used in former times.
Whakamārama: I riro te whenua mo tauiwi i raro i te mana o te Karauna.
Scope Note: Land taken in retribution for a wrong doing.
Whakamārama: He momo rākau kei ngā ngāhere o ngā maunga e tupu ana. He rahirahi ngā peka. He mātatoru te tupu o ngā rau pērā i te kiekie, ā, e tapahia ana hei raranga.

Scope Note: A tree of forests in mountainous country with thin branches ending in a bunch of leaves. There are different kinds in the North Island (D. latifolium) and the South Island (D. traversii). The latter especially is used by weavers. Dracophyllum traversii.
Whakamārama: He rākau porowhita. Ka whakatākotokotoria kia ngāwari ai te tō i te waka ki uta, i te whenua rānei.
Scope Note: Rollers upon which waka/canoes where dragged overland at portages.
Whakamārama: Te āhua o tētahi mea ka kitea e te kanohi, ko whero, ko pango, ko mā.
Scope Note: Use for general resources on marine life (both animals and plants).
Whakamārama: He rākau kei te takutai moana e tupu ana. I te mea he repe noni kei ngā rau, ka hāpiapia. Ko ngā pua he mā, he māwhero ngā kōiraira. He porouri ngā hua.
Scope Note: A coastal tree with sticky leaves marked by prominent oil glands. The flowers are white, dotted with pink and the berry is purple. Myoporum laetum.
Whakamārama: Kei runga i te rae tēnei tā moko.
Scope Note: These are the two triangular tattooed areas either side of the centre line of the forehead.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā uri a Tāne pērā i te aitanga pepeke, i te mokomoko me ētahi atu.
Scope Note: A collective term for many invertebrate animals, including insects, worms, centipedes, gastropods and various larvae.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā Uri a Tāne pērā i te aitanga pepeke me ētahi atu. E ai ki ngā kōrero tuku iho, he kararehe, he tipua, ko tōna hanga he whakamataku.

Scope Note: A collective term for many invertebrate animals including spiders, insects, centipedes, and various larvae, but also including reptiles. It is also used to refer to a creature or supernatural being whose form incites fear.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā Uri rērere a Tāne, he katete ngā tinana. He pī, he rango, he wāpi me ēra atu.
Scope Note: A category of flying insects with stout bodies, including the native burrowing bees, native wasps and brachyceran flies.
Scope Note: Rhythmic chants with spontaneous actions; a type of haka, e.g. Ka mate, ka mate.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti he rite ki te miromiro engari he āhua hāurakaho te poho.
Scope Note: A small bird resembling the miromiro/North Island tomtit but with yellowish buff colour on the breast. Petroica macrocephala macrocephala.
Whakamārama: Ko te ngohe he mahi ako mā te tauira.
Whakamārama: He tuna nui nō te moana, he pango ōrangi te kiri, he rarahi ngā karu.
Scope Note: A large marine eel with a blue black skin and a large eye. Conger verreauxi.
Whakamārama: Kei ngā tahataha o te rae ki runga i ngā whatu enei tā moko.
Scope Note: These tattoo patterns comprise the triangular areas on either side of the forehead above the eyebrows and either side of the ngākaipikirau.
Whakamārama: He āhua rite ki te kōauau tēnei taonga. Kotahi noa te rerekē, ko tētahi pito he piko. Ka whakatāngihia ma te waha me te ihu hoki.
Scope Note: This instrument is similar to the kōauau/traditional flute with one difference being that one end is turned upward. It can be blown by either the mouth or the nose.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti, pōkai atu ki te tāhuna. He hina te tuarā, he mā te poho. E takawiri kē ana te ngutu ki te taha matau.
Scope Note: A small bird which flocks on the shore. It is grey above and white below. It differs from all other birds in having the bill twisted to the right. Anarhynchus frontalis.
Scope Note: A type of lattice work pattern.
Whakamārama: Ko te nīkau ake o Aotearoa, ko ngā rauhuru hei rauwhare.
Scope Note: A palm that is indigenous (native) to New Zealand. The fronds were used for thatch. Rhopalostylis sapida.
Whakamārama: He mahi nā ngā tohunga, kia puta ai ngā tohu.
Scope Note: A divination ceremony to predict future events. Small sticks and fern stalks were used.
Whakamārama: Tērā mea tenoa he mea whakapoi, whakanoa hoki taua mea ra te tapu.
Scope Note: Free from tapu or any other restriction.
Whakamārama: Te tirohanga mo te noho pūmau a ngā iwi.
Whakamārama: Ko te nūpepa he pukapuka kawe kōrero e pā ana ki ngā kaupapa o te wā me te aha noa ka tāngia i ia rā i ia wiki rānei.
Scope Note: Can be used for examples of newspapers or for works about newspapers.
Whakamārama: Kei roto i tēnei kaupapa ngā matū tino taketake e hangaia ai te ao tūroa, mai i te noke ki te whetū. E tū mataara ana a Rūaumoko hei kaitiaki.
Scope Note: The world of matter, encompassing all original substances that make up the earth, from worms to stars. Rūaumoko is the guardian of the world of matter.
Whakamārama: Kei te pau te hau o te tangata tata rawa mai ki tōna matenga, ka puta ko tōna inoi, tōna hiahia me tōna kōrero whakamutunga. Katahi ka mate.
Scope Note: The dying breath of a person instilled with final wishes.
Whakamārama: Te pai o te noho o tētahi whenua ina tirohia te kaha o tana waihanga me tana whakapau i ngā taonga hoko me ngā ratonga, me te nui o te moni e wātea ana ki a ia.
Scope Note: The system of production, distribution and consumption of goods and services.
Whakamārama: Ko te mahi whakapakari pūtea, te whakapakari ohaoha, te whakapakari ūmanga, te mahi whai pūtea i te ao hurihuri nei.
Scope Note: Economic development and growth including capacity building, increasing economic gains, etc.
Whakamārama: Ko te kaupapa tēnei o te whakanoanga me te whakaratonga o te ngaki o te whenua.
Scope Note: The science of the production and distribution of wealth.
Whakamārama: He manu moana, he rahi, he hāurapango te tuarā, he hāuratea te puku. Hei te takurua, ka paopao. He huahua nā ngā iwi o Te Ika a Māui.

Scope Note: A large seabird with blackish brown feathers, paler below. It breeds in winter and the chicks were gathered and preserved as an important food preserve for North Island iwi. Pterodroma macroptera.
Whakamārama: He momo wīwi. He angiangi, he monamona ngā rau. Kei ngā pūkenga wai o te taha moana e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A rush with fragile jointed leaves which is found on flooded tidal flats behind beaches. Leptocarpus simplex.
Whakamārama: Ka mahi te tokorua i ētahi mahi kia tokomauri ai, pērā i te kuhu i te ure tū ki te tara, ka werowero ai ā tuhaina rawatia te tātea
Whakamārama: Ki te ora te tangata, ka pai tōna wairua, tōna tinana, tōna hinengaro, tōna ngākau hoki.
Scope Note: If a person is exceptionally well, so will he/she be well spiritually, physically, mentally and personally.
Whakamārama: He momo rākau nā Tū, ka taea te tango o te tara.
Scope Note: A war spear with a detachable point.
Whakamārama: Ka whānau te tamaiti, ka titoa e te whaea, e te matua, e ngā tupuna rānei kia ori mai te pepe.
Scope Note: A lullaby composed for a baby by its parents or grandparents.
Whakamārama: Te tino tīmatanga o ngā mea katoa, arā, te hanga o te ao tukupū.
Scope Note: The metaphysical study of the origin and nature of the universe. Use for works about the creation of the world and/or the universe.
Whakamārama: He rite ki te kōauau tēnei taonga engari ko ngā wenewene noho piri tonu, ā, ka hanga mai i te kakau o te hue.
Scope Note: This instrument, traditionally made from the neck of the gourd, is similar to the kōauau/traditional flute but the finger holes are close together.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tarutaru ngāwari ngā tāta.
Scope Note: A collective term for herbaceous plants without woody stems. Includes grasses.
Scope Note: Plants used as vegetables.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo otaota kei runga i ngā rākau e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A collective term for epiphytic plants. Epiphytes grow attached to, but are not fed by, other plants, such as trees.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo otaota tupu i roto i te waimāori.
Scope Note: A collective term for plants that live in freshwater.
Whakamārama: Te wāhi hei nohoanga mo ngā whānau, hapū, iwi.
Scope Note: A village occupied by a group of people who are related to each other.
Whakamārama: I hangaia ahuriri, ā, he maha ngā ika i mau.
Scope Note: Fish weir or enclosure set in a stream to trap fresh-water fish on their annual migration to sea to spawn.
Whakamārama: He wāhi whakaruru mō ngā tāngata kāore i te whawhai i te wā o te pakanga.
Scope Note: A place of refuge for non-combatants in time of war.
Whakamārama: He pā nunui, he maioro nunui hoki i tēnei momo pā.
Scope Note: A huge village made up mainly of complex earthworks.
Scope Note: Can be used for examples of websites or for works about websites.
Whakamārama: Ko te ika nui rawa o ngā ika ihu roroa, engari he ihu paraha.
Scope Note: The largest of the billfishes, with the spear distinctly flattened. Unlike other billfishes it has no pelvic fins. Xiphias gladius.
Scope Note: Can be used for examples of anthologies or for works about anthologies.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tā ēnei e piko ana ki ngā pāpāringa.
Scope Note: These are the cheek spirals of facial tattoos.
Whakamārama: He kaho kei roto i te waka, kei waenganui i te rauawa me te kaunaroa.
Scope Note: A batten on the inside of a canoe, between the hull and the rauawa.
Whakamārama: He pūkohu rahi, kei te ngahere mākūkū e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A large moss resembling a young pine seedling. It grows in stands in damp forest. Dawsonia superba.
Whakamārama: He rākau rite ki te kawaka. Kia pakari, kua rite ngā rau ki te inohi.
Scope Note: A tall tree resembling the kawaka, with a cone shaped head of spreading branches and fernlike foliage with scale-like adult leaves. Libocedrus bidwillii.
Whakamārama: He taonga whakatangitangi tēnei hanga mai i te rākau, ā, no te whānau hoki o Tūmatakōkiri, he rerekē tana āhuatanga ki a te pūkaea. He taonga pao pao i te ringa.

Scope Note: This instrument is made of wood and belongs to the Tūmatakōkiri classification of Māori instruments even though it differs visibly in shape and playing techniques to that of the pūkaea/trumpet. It is a type of drum.
Scope Note: Name of the religion founded by the prophet Te Ua Haumēne.
Whakamārama: He kararehe noho ngahere, noho wao, he parauri kiwikiwi ngā huruhuru ngerungeru, he nunui ngā karu, ka taea e ia tana whiore roa te takai ki te rākau, he kararehe haere pō.

Scope Note: Brush tailed possums were introduced into New Zealand in 1837 to establish a fur trade. The possum has a thick bushy tail, a pointed snout and long marsupial ears. Typically a night creature, the possum can wrap its tail around trees to move about. Trichosurus vulpecula.
Whakamārama: Ko te pukapuka tapu a te whakapono Karaitiana.
Scope Note: The Christian Bible, a religious text. This heading can be used for examples of Bibles or for works about Bibles.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti nō te moana. He hina ōrangi te tuarā, he mā te puku. He rite ki te tītī wainui.
Scope Note: A small shearwater, brown above and white below, with a very loud call. Pachyptila cittata.
Whakamārama: Ko te tahunga ahi, o runga o te waka. He kerepeti te papa.
Scope Note: A fireplace made of pressed clay, set in a waka/canoe.
Whakamārama: He momo whakairo e pā ana ki tētahi momo tohorā.
Scope Note: The depiction of whales on carvings.
Te Pakanga Tuatahi o Te Ao
Whakamārama: He pakanga te pakanga ahakoa ko wai ahakoa ki hea.
Scope Note: All types of warfare, including intertribal.
Whakamārama: Ko te āhuatanga o tēnei whakairo, e ōrite ana ki te niho kuri.
Scope Note: 'Dog tooth' notches in carving.
Whakamārama: He taonga tākaro i hangaia ai ki te toetoe, i uhia ki te anga.
Scope Note: Kites made from rushes, etc., stretched on a frame.
Scope Note: Rain capes made by attaching leaf strips, hukahuka, to a woven foundation.
Scope Note: New Zealanders of European descent.
Whakamārama: He tāne, he wāhine rānei kua neke atu ōna tau i ō te tamariki, i ō te taiohi, engari kāore anō kia koroua rawa, kia kuia rawa.
Scope Note: Mature people aged between young adults and the elderly. See also: Taitamariki (Youth, aged about 16-21) and Kaumātua (Elders).
Whakamārama: Kei waho o te whare ngā pakitara, arā kei raro iho i te tuanui.
Scope Note: The outside walls of the meeting house.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā kōrero parau a te Māori.
Scope Note: Fictional stories of Māori as opposed to historical or legendary. Modern fiction. This heading can be used for examples of fiction or for works about fiction.
Whakamārama: He pūrākau i tuhia ki te pikitia.

Scope Note: Works in graphic novel format, including 'true' stories and fiction. Can be used for examples of graphic novels and for works about graphic novels, or, for works about biographies and life stories in graphic novel format.
Whakamārama: He whare mō runga i ngā waka nunui.
Scope Note: The deckhouse of a large waka/canoe.
Whakamārama: He momo whakairo tēnei, e pikopiko haere ana te āhua.
Scope Note: A rolling interconnecting spiral pattern in carvings.
Whakamārama: Hanga mai i te kōiwi ūpokohue, he taonga warua, paoa hoki te pākuru.
Scope Note: Made from the bone of the pilot whale, this type of instrument was a percussion instrument which used a scraping and tapping motion.
Whakamārama: He ika matatuhi, māwhero kita. He tohu karaka kei ngā tinana o ētahi. He iti noa iho te ūpoko engari he tino roroa ngā pakihau taha.

Scope Note: A large schooling fish of bright pink colour, sometimes with orange markings. The head is rather small but the pectoral fins are very long. The dorsal fin is very spiny. Caprodon longimanus.
Whakamārama: Te ako ki te pānui pukapuka.
Scope Note: Works containing material for instruction and practice in reading te reo Māori. Can be used for examples of readers or for works about readers.
Whakamārama: He pānui o te tangihanga o tētahi ika kua tāngia e te whānau pani i te nūpepa.
Scope Note: Notices advising the death of a person placed in a newspaper by the bereaved family containing a few personal details. See also: Maimai aroha (Obituaries).
Whakamārama: He pānui hei whakaatu i tētahi rawa, i tētahi ratonga ki te iwi whānui.
Scope Note: Public promotions of products or services; advertisements and public notices.
Whakamārama: He waiata pakupaku, katakata, ako i ngā tamariki.
Scope Note: A short poem, often sung and usually humorous.
Whakamārama: He hāhi, he wānanga Māori o roto o te Rohe Pōtae.
Scope Note: A Māori religious response to the opening up of the Rohe Pōtae (King Country).
Whakamārama: E hora atu nei te papa i runga i a Papatūānuku kei rō wharepuni.
Scope Note: The floor of the meeting house.
Whakamārama: Te tane nāna i puta ai tētahi tamaiti ki te ao, nāna rānei ia i whakatipu.
Scope Note: Fathers and older male relatives, sometimes thought of as teachers. See also Koroua (Elderly men, Grandfathers).
Whakamārama: He nui ngā toa i tētahi wāhi.
Scope Note: A complex of retail shops.
Whakamārama: Ka tuku kōrero mā te reo irirangi, te pouaka whakaata, te kiriata, te ipurangi, te ao pāpāho rānei.
Scope Note: Mass communication through the medium of radio, television, film, print, Internet and mass media. See also: Ao pāpāho/News media.
Whakamārama: He momo wahie te papaka kei raro iho i te wharepuni engari i runga i te papa kei waenganui hoki enei wahie i ngā poupou.
Scope Note: The horizontal narrow boards or skirting boards placed below the carved panels close to the floor of the meeting house.
Whakamārama: He ingoa nui mō ngā pāpaka.
Scope Note: A general term for crabs.
Whakamārama: Ko te papa hei kāinga mo te mana whenua.
Scope Note: A settlement or village built on land, which the people dwelling there are related to.
Whakamārama: Ko te papakupu he pukapuka whakamārama i te tikanga o ngā kupu.
Scope Note: Can be used for examples of dictionaries or for works about dictionaries.
Whakamārama: He rākau ririki, he ngitangita ngā hua, ka maumau ngā manu itiiti i te hāpiapia.
Scope Note: A small tree with large leaves bearing sticky masses of fruit which often entrap small birds. Pisonia brunoniana.
Whakamārama: He manu nō te aumoana, he ōrangi-hina te tuarā, he mā te poho. He rite ki te tītī wainui engari he rahi ake.
Scope Note: A seabird with grey/blue plumage above and white below, similar to the tītī wainui/fairy prion but larger. Pachyptila vittata.
Whakamārama: Ko te whakairo tēnei i runga i te tatau.
Scope Note: The carved lintel at the top of the door.
Whakamārama: Te wāhanga o te kāwanatanga koia kei te hanga i ngā ture.
Scope Note: Parliament, legislative body of government.
Whakamārama: He rakiraki hāura, kōtiwhatiwha. Ko tōna tohu ko te mā o te kanohi, me te tāhei pango o te karu.
Scope Note: A duck with mottled brown plumage distinguished by a white face with a dark stripe across the eye. Anas superciliosa.
Whakamārama: He otaota ririki, toropapa te tupu.
Scope Note: A small plantain growing close to the ground. Plantago spathulata.
Whakamārama: He ika ririki, he hina kākonu, he tāhekeheke whāiti kei te tinana.
Scope Note: A small silver grey fish with narrow vertical bands. Girella tricuspidata.
Whakamārama: He tangata e patupatua ana, e tūkinotia ana, kua murua rānei ana taonga, tana kāinga e tētahi atu.
Scope Note: Any aggrieved person subjected to violence, ill treatment or wrongful dispossession of lands and properties by another party.
Whakamārama: He pātaka kai tēnei momo whare.
Scope Note: A building used for storing food.
Whakamārama: He momo rākau, rarahi ngā tawhera, tae ana ki te iwa ngā tawheraiti. Kei ngā wāhi mākūkū, marumaru e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A tree with large compound leaves with up to nine leaflets each. It likes damp and shade. Schefflera digitata.
Whakamārama: He rakiraki iti, he hāura ngā huruhuru, he āhua rite ki te pārera. Ko te māhunga o te tame he porouri, he kāriki whakaataata hoki.
Scope Note: A small duck with brown feathers, rather like a mallard. The head of the male is dark brown with green reflections. Anas aucklandica chlorotis.
Whakamārama: He waiata taititotito, i takea i ngā kōrero hahani, i te kanga, i te kai-ūpoko rānei.
Scope Note: Abusive and derogatory songs.
Whakamārama: Ko te pātiki he ika noho moana, noho awa rānei, he papa, he porohita te āhua o te hanga o te tinana.
Scope Note: A diamond shaped flounder, mottled green/brown above and white below. Rhombosolea plebeia. Not to be used for general works covering many species of flounder.
Whakamārama: He ingoa nui mō ngā pātītī itiiti, he rerekē i ngā pātītī rarahi pērā i te toetoe.
Scope Note: A general term for small grasses, as distinguished from toetoe/tussocks.
Whakamārama: He otaota rārāpiri, he tūtū ngā rau. Ko te hua he ririki, he karaka, he reka.
Scope Note: A small creeping plant with prickly leaves and a small sweet orange berry. Styphelia nesophila.
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tū. I tāraia ki te kōhatu, ki te paiore, ki te parāoa rānei. He patu anō hei pehu aruhe, hei whakangāwari muka.
Scope Note: A short club used as a weapon, made of stone, wood or bone. Other patu are used to soften fernroot and flax fibre.
Whakamārama: He patu i tāraia ki te ōnewa.
Scope Note: A patu made from the stone ōnewa/basalt.
Whakamārama: He patu i tāraia ki te iwi parāoa.
Scope Note: A patu made from whalebone.
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tū, he patu tapawhā.
Scope Note: A wooden hand weapon with a ridge down the blade. Single-handed weapon that was designed to be used with a downward clubbing stroke.

Whakamārama: He ope wairua ko te karahiwi, ko te tihi maunga rānei tōna kāinga, he kiritea, he urukehu, he iwi tino tapu. Kia tau mai te kohu, ka rangona e kōrerorero ana, e waiata ana, e whakatangi kōauau ana, e aha ana hoki.

Scope Note: The fairy-like creatures of the forests and mountain tops who are regarded as supernatural beings. They have light coloured skin and red or fair hair and are considered highly tapu. They can be heard talking, singing, and playing musical flutes as they are active at night time and when the mist is heavy enough to shield them from the light.
Whakamārama: He kaimoana piri ki te toka. He pango te hua, he ūiraira, he ātaahua te anga.
Scope Note: A large limpet-shaped gastropod with a black animal and iridescent shell interior. Haliotis iris.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tā moko ēnei e heke iho ki te kauwae.
Scope Note: These tattoos curve in under the chin.
Whakamārama: He otaota rārāpiri ki te kiri o te rākau. He rite ki te pātītī ngā raurau. Hei te koanga ka puta ngā pua ririki, kaho.
Scope Note: An epiphytic orchid with matted roots creeping on bark. It has grassy leaves and stems with small yellow flowers in Spring. Earina mucronata.
Whakamārama: He momo whakakai tēnei hanga mai i te pounamu engari ko tana āhua, e ōrite ana ki te kararehe, te pekapeka.
Scope Note: An ornamental adornment resembling the small native bat which it is named after. Usually made of greenstone.
Whakamārama: Ko te pēke te whare tiaki moni.
Whakamārama: He tamaiti i ōna tau tuatahi ki tēnei ao, he tamaiti tino nohinohi.
Scope Note: Very young children in their first year of birth, or babies. See also: Tamariki nohinohi (Toddlers)
Whakamārama: He kōrero e pā ana ki ngā tūtohu whenua o tētahi rohe, o tētahi iwi, otirā, e kōrero anō hoki i tōna rangatira, i tōna mana.
Scope Note: Short recitations which point out significant features within particular areas of tribal boundaries, and which also denote the prestige of chiefs and traits of kin groups.
Whakamārama: He momo haka tēnei engari e mau ana te kaihaka i te tewhatewha.
Scope Note: A type of haka performed with the use of a weapon called a tewhatewha.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo huruhuru whenua rite ki te parenako. Ko te nuinga kei runga i ngā rākau e tupu ana.
Scope Note: General term for several types of spleenworts, ferns of the genus Asplenium. A general term for ferns resembling parenako/shining spleenwort, most of which grow on trees. Asplenium spp.
Whakamārama: He momo petako he mangu ngā tātā, he koikoi ngā tawheraiti. Kei runga i ngā rākau e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A drooping epiphytic fern with black stems and pointed simple leaflets. Asplenium polyodon.
Whakamārama: Kia tapahia ētahi rākau, kua rere te pia, kua heke te tarawai, pērā i te kauri. Hei pia ngaungau, hei whakakakara i ngā hinu panipani.
Scope Note: Gum exuded from trees, used as a masticatory, or for scenting oils etc.
Whakamārama: Ko te pia o te mānuka , ko te tarawai e inumia ana e te ngārara, ka marere te tatahe, hei whakareka kai.
Scope Note: Honeydew from the mānuka produced by the mānuka scale insect. It was eaten as a sort of manna.
Whakamārama: He ngārara waewae pepeke, he pango. Kia pouri kua waiata.
Scope Note: A black singing cricket. Teleogryllus commodus.
Whakamārama: He tatata mangaeka tatara, engari he whakarei e tapiri ana.
Scope Note: A patterned garment made from undressed flax.
Whakamārama: Te hī ika i te matau me te taura.
Scope Note: Catching fish with a hook and line.
Scope Note: Polystichum richardii, the common shield fern.
Scope Note: Fern shoots used in cooking.

Whakamārama: Ko te taipū te kainga o te pīngao. He tino taonga mō ngā mahi raranga. E mata ana ka katohia, ka pūpū, kā whakairi i te wāhi hauhau e kore e whitikia e te rā. Waiho kia maroke, kia ngāwhā.
Scope Note: A sand dwelling plant with golden-yellow leaves prized for weaving of decorative kete/baskets. Desmoschoenus spiralis.
Whakamārama: He roma e rere whakararo ana, ka ngaro atu ki te ana.
Scope Note: Streams which disappear underground into caves.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo kaimoana, e rua ngā anga.
Scope Note: A general term for bivalved shellfish, especially those gathered for food.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti o te ngahere, he rite ki te mōhua, he hāura ngā huruhuru.
Scope Note: A small brown forest bird. Mohoua novaeseelandiae.
Whakamārama: He manu pīrere. Hei te koanga ka tau mai ki Aotearoa. He kārikirino te tuarā, he mā, he kawakawa mōhinuhinu ngā tāhei o te puku.
Scope Note: A migrant bird with metallic green plumage on the back and the underparts white finely barred with dark glossy green. Chrysococcyx lucidus.
Whakamārama: He kawariki iti, he kōwhai ngā pua. Ko ngā rau he ririki, he pūhuruhuru.
Scope Note: A small buttercup with yellow flowers and small hairy leaves. Ranunculus hirtus.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā otaota hāwere kei runga i te rākau e tupu ana. Ko te wai o te rākau tana kai. He kita ngā pua.
Scope Note: A general term for the parasitic mistletoes of the genera Peraxilla and Trilepidia. Now rare because of opossum damage, these epiphytic parasites have brightly-coloured flowers.
Whakamārama: He otaota totoro te tupu. He taratara, he porohita te hanga o ngā puarere.
Scope Note: A creeping plant with a spiky, ball-like seedhead. Acaena spp.

Whakamārama: Nā Tahupōtiki Wiremu Rātana i whakatū te Hāhi Rātana.

Scope Note: Services provided to the tribe, such as health, vocational and informational services.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā taha o te waka, aukahatia ai ki te kaunaroa. He whakairo ētahi.
Scope Note: The side-pieces of a canoe, often carved, which are lashed to the kaunaroa/hull.
Whakamārama: He mea āwhina i ngā mahi.
Whakamārama: He otaota pōruru kei te takutai moana e tupu ana. He mā ngā puia, kotahi anō ki te tātā.
Scope Note: A bushy coastal herb with solitary white flowers with five petals. Linum monogynum.
Whakamārama: He rākau kakara ngā rau. E mata ana, he tawheratoru, he nihoniho ngā rau. Kia pakari kua toitū kua tawherarua rānei.
Scope Note: A tree with smooth-edged and aromatic leaves. Juvenile leaves are 3 lobed and deeply toothed. Adult leaves are one or two lobed. Pseudopanax edgerleyi.
Whakamārama: He mauwha, kei te Tai Rāwhiti anake e tupu ana. He kōwhai ngā pua. He rite ngā rau ki o te houhere.
Scope Note: A shrubby daisy with yellow flowers found only in Te Tai Rāwhiti/Gisborne District. Brachyglottis perdicioides.
Whakamārama: He huruhuru manu, ka puhipuhi, hei whakapaipai i ngā makawe.
Scope Note: Clusters of feathers worn as hair ornaments.
Whakamārama: He otaota rārāpiri, rite ki te peka ā waka, engari he whānui ake ngā rau. I te Ngahuru, ka puta ngā pua, he mā, he kakara rawa atu.
Scope Note: An epiphytic orchid with matted roots like peka ā waka/bamboo orchid but with broader leaves and strongly scented white flowers in the Autumn. Earina autumnalis.
Whakamārama: He whara tupu i ngā hawai. Pūpūria ai ngā rau hei whakapuru, ko ngā kōnehu hei komeke.
Scope Note: A rush which grows in shallow open water. The soft leaves were used for thatch and the pollen for food. Typha orientalis.

Whakamārama: He whara, rite ki te harakeke, engari ko ngā rau rite kē ki o te raupō. Mumura ana te whero o ngā pua. Ko te Motu o Manawa Tāwhi tōna kāinga tūturu, engari e whāia ana i ēnei rā hei whakatō ki nga tinaku.

Scope Note: A coastal flax-like plant with a flat leaf like the raupō/bulrush, and a bright red flower head like a toothbrush. It is found naturally only at the Poor Knights Islands, but is now widely cultivated in gardens. Xeronema callistemon.
Whakamārama: Kei waenganui i te ihu me ngā ngutu ēnei momo tā moko.
Scope Note: This is the part of the facial tattoo on the upper lip area.
Whakamārama: Ko te rā o te waka
Scope Note: A sail for a waka/canoe.
Whakamārama: He rite ki te pōrutu tēnei taonga engari kei te pae tonu tana waha.
Scope Note: This instrument is similar to the pōrutu/flute except that it has a transverse blowing hole.
Whakamārama: He whakakai te rei puta hangai mai i te niho tohorā.
Scope Note: A neck adornment made from the tooth of a sperm whale.
Whakamārama: He otaota ririki, rārāpiri. He rite ki te pānakenake engari he itiiti iho ngā pua, he maheni nga rau.
Scope Note: A small creeping plant with small white flowers and smooth leaves. Selliera radicans.
Whakamārama: He otaota ririki, he rite ngā pua ki o te rīwai. He pango ngā hua.
Scope Note: A small plant with a flower like the potato and a black berry. Solanum americanum.
Whakamārama: He tirohanga ki te mita me te tangi o te reo o tēnā iwi, o tēnā iwi.

Scope Note: Use for works about iwi/tribal dialects or works featuring a specific tribal language. Use this heading in addition to the iwi or hapū name from the Iwi and Hapū Names List if known - http://iwihapu.natlib.govt.nz/iwi-hapu/.
Whakamārama: Te reo o te iwi Māori.
Scope Note: The language of the indigenous people of New Zealand. Use for works about the Māori language.
Whakamārama: Ko te reo Māori me tētahi atu reo anō.
Scope Note: To be used for bilingual material when it is in te reo Māori and another language.
Whakamārama: He tino rahi tēnei mangō, he roroa ngā pihapiha. Kautere noa ai ki te kimi i ana kai, i ngā ngārara tino ririki o te aumoana.
Scope Note: A very large shark with long gill slits. It feeds on plankton and is seen floating at the surface of the sea. Cetorhinus maximus.
Whakamārama: He whāinga kupu, he whakahēnga rānei nā te kaikōrero i ngā āhuatanga o te wā.
Scope Note: Social commentary or criticism delivered in Māori.
Whakamārama: He momo tā moko ōrite ki ngā hihi o te rā e toro atu mai i te waha ki te kauwae.
Scope Note: Facial tattoo patterns resembling rays which extend from the mouth to the chin.
Whakamārama: He otaota rite ki te mānihi engari he whāiti iho ngā rau. Tipu ai i ngā hāroto. Ko ngā rau kei roto i te wai he roroa ake i ngā mea e rewa ana i runga.
Scope Note: A water plant with much submerged leaves narrower and longer than those which float on the surface. Potamogeton cheesemanii.
Whakamārama: He rārangi kāreti e tūhono ana tētahi ki tētahi, ka kumea haeretia e te waka whai pūkaha o mua, e tētahi atu momo pūkaha rānei.
Whakamārama: Ko te reta he kōrero ka tuhia, ka tukuna atu ki tētahi.
Scope Note: Can be used for examples of letters and for works about letters.
Whakamārama: He otaota ririki, hora noa ai i runga i te wai whakaroto. He pūwhero.
Scope Note: A small floating plant forming dense reddish carpets on still water. Azolla spp.
Whakamārama: He rākau tino teitei, pūhihi hoki. He roroa, he whāiti, he nihoniho, ngā rau, he kārikihina a waho. Ko ngā pua he ura, he pūhui.
Scope Note: A tall slender tree with long narrow, toothed leaves which are glaucous (have a bloom) underneath. The red brown flowers grow in a bunch and have long spiky anthers. Knightia excelsa.
Whakamārama: He rākau tino roa nō te wao a Tāne. E mata ana he kupakupa ngā rārā, he taratara ngā rau. Kia pakari, kua whakamatika. He rite ngā hua ki o te kāhikatea.
Scope Note: A very tall forest tree. The young tree has drooping branchlets with spiky leaves. The adult foliage is more erect. The fruit is orange like that of the kahikatea. Dacrydium cupressinum.
Whakamārama: He rimutai rarahi, mātotoru, pūareare, hāuratea. Kei ngā toka ā tai e tupu ana. Ka pōhahatia hei putunga mō ngā huahua tītī.
Scope Note: A large brown seaweed found on rocky coasts. The middle of the thallus (plant body) is like a honeycomb. Large pieces were split open and used to store muttonbirds. Durvillea spp.
Whakamārama: He momo rimutai, he kārikiuri, he itiiti, he rite ki ngā rārā o te rimu mata.
Scope Note: A small green seaweed which resembles the branchlets of the young rimu tree. Caulerpa brownii.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo otaota e tupu ana i te tai, pērā i te rimurimu, i te karengo.
Scope Note: Marine plants including seaweeds and other plants that grow in the sea such as karepō/eelgrass.
Whakamārama: Kei te mau tonu te whenua e te tangata whenua i ngā parekura.
Scope Note: Ownership of land maintained and retained by force.
Scope Note: Name of the religion founded by the prophet Te Kooti Arikirangi Te Turuki.
Whakamārama: Kei te kauwae raro ēnei momo tā moko.
Scope Note: These tattoos are in the area of the lower jaw.
Whakamārama: He manu noho i te māheuheu, i te ngahere. He hinatea te poho, he hāurahina te tuarā.
Scope Note: A small common bird of scrub and forest. It is pale grey below and darker above. Gerygone igata.
Whakamārama: He mahi ā iwi, ā hapū, ā tangata. Ko te ritenga patu manu tētahi.
Scope Note: Methods of applying cultural practices, e.g. methods of bird snaring. Can also apply to Western ideas of rites and rituals.
Whakamārama: Ko te rito o te nīkau, hei kai.
Scope Note: The heart shoot of the nīkau, used as a vegetable.
Whakamārama: Ko te rito o te tī kāuka, hei kai.
Scope Note: The heart shoot of the cabbage tree, used as a vegetable.
Whakamārama: He Aitanga Pēpeke. He rōroa ngā tinana me ngā waewae pēpeke. Rite tonu ki ngā rārā e nohoia ana.
Scope Note: Stick insects and mantids. These are large insects with slender legs and a distinctive slow gait.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā roimata o te toroa te tauira mo te tukutuku.
Scope Note: The tukutuku/lattice work design resembling the tears of the albatross.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā kai katoa kia kore ai e pirau, kia kore ai rānei e tere pirau.

Scope Note: Cooked and uncooked preserved foodstuffs, including frozen foods. See also: Hinu kai for cooked foods preserved in oil or fat. See also: Huahua for uncooked preserved fish and game. See also: Toroī for fermented foods.
Whakamārama: Na Rona te pō, na Rona te ao hei aronga mo te marama.
Scope Note: The personification of the moon.
Whakamārama: He mea whakaora i te tīnana, te hinengaro me te wairua, te rongoā Māori.
Scope Note: Holistic and traditional methods of healing, enhancing and enriching wellbeing using natural medicines and/or practices.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo mate e pā ana ki ngā mea whakahe i te tangata.
Scope Note: Covers all types of drug abuse. Use a narrower term where appropriate. See narrower terms for specific drug abuse, e.g. P abuse, marijuana abuse, glue sniffing.
Whakamārama: Ko ia te atua o ngā kai tipu i te māra, ā, he kaitiaki hoki ia o te rangimarie me te whare kai.
Scope Note: The personification of peace, the god of cultivated foods and the guardian of the dining room.
Whakamārama: He whakarauikatanga tāngata Māori. I ēnei rā he rōpū whakarite kaupapa.
Scope Note: A group or company of Māori. In a modern sense a society, group or association. Includes Māori trusts such as the New Zealand Māori Wardens Association and Māori Women's Welfare League.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo rangapū katoa o te Paremata ki waho, ki roto rānei, kia whāia tonu ngā kaupapa tōrangapū.
Scope Note: Political parties and groups, who sit inside or outside Parliament, that seek to achieve a political objective.
Whakamārama: He wahie tēnei taonga. E orite ana tana reo ki te "Jew's harp".

Whakamārama: Ko te pakitara te roro kei reira te tatau me te matapihi kei roro hoki i te mahau.
Scope Note: The back wall of the porch of the meeting house.
Whakamārama: Ko te mātauranga o ngā mahi rorohiko.
Scope Note: The study of computer technology.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā kēmu rorohiko katoa.
Scope Note: A general heading for all computer and video games. Can be used for examples of computer/video games or for works about computer/video games.
Whakamārama: He momo waiata whakakaha i te koi o te hinengaro a ngā mahi o ngā ringaringa.
Scope Note: Hand game chants to develop hand-eye co-ordination skills.
Whakamārama: He puna nui wai Māori, wai moana hoki.
Scope Note: Freshwater and saltwater lakes.
Whakamārama: He momo atua a Ruakapanga. Māna e tiki te mātauranga ki te hanga whare whakairo mai i a Rangitamaku.
Scope Note: A demigod who climbed to Rangitamaku to retrieve the knowledge of house building.
Whakamārama: Ko ia te atua o te rū whenua, ā, te pōtiki hoki o te tini whāioio.
Scope Note: The god of earthquakes and the youngest of the family.
Whakamārama: E ruku ana te tangata i te wai ki te hōpu kōura, ā, he momo mahinga kai te ruku kōura.
Whakamārama: He otaota hāura. He whāiti, he pakini ngā rau, he pūngarungaru ngā tapa.
Scope Note: A brown spreading plant with narrow notched leaves with wavy edges. Rumex flexuosus.
Whakamārama: He rōpū rangatira, he kaumātua rānei ka noho ki te whakahaere i ngā take a te iwi.
Scope Note: Iwi organisations and urban Māori organisations.
Whakamārama: He tito ngā kōrero e puta mai ana.

Scope Note: A song or ditty, usually amorous, accompanied by gestures.
Whakamārama: He manu rere ahiahi. He koukou tana tangi. He hāura kōtiwhatiwha. He pūrerehua tana kai.
Scope Note: A small brown owl commonly seen at dusk feeding on moths and other insects. Ninox novaeseelandiae.
Whakamārama: He whakataetae kapa haka kei tēnā rohe kei tēnā takiwā, engari kotahi ngahuru noa iho ngā tangata kei ia kapa.
Scope Note: Contemporary kapa haka regional competitions.
Whakamārama: He whakataetae kapa haka, engari hotahi ngahuru ma rua ngā tangata kei ia kapa.
Scope Note: Contemporary kapa haka national competitions.
Whakamārama: Ānei ētahi whakamārama mo tēnei mea te "tā": te tāia o te kauae me ngā ngutu hei moko kauae, ka tāia te kaiwhakairo i te rākau, ka tāia te kaipeita i tana pikitia.
Scope Note: Use for examples relating to "strike": the chiselling of the chin and lips for tattooing, the carver carving wood, bone or pounamu/greenstone, the artist drawing and painting.
Whakamārama: Ko te tā moko mahi i te ngira he taonga i hangaia i te rino hei tā moko i te kiri.
Scope Note: Tattooing using contemporary methods and tools. See also Tā moko (Uhi), the term for Tattooing (Traditional)
Whakamārama: Ko te tā moko mahi i te uhi he taonga i whaowhaoa hei tā moko i te kiri.
Scope Note: Tattooing using traditional methods and tools. See also Tā moko (Tā ngira), the term for Tattooing (Contemporary)
Scope Note: Gourd containers used for storing food.
Whakamārama: He kauaeroa hei whakamoke i te hoariri.
Scope Note: A small fighting force concealed to ambush a fighting force of the enemy.
Whakamārama: He momo tāwhiti, e mau ana i te manu.
Scope Note: A trap to snare birds.
Scope Note: Electronics, a branch of physics.
Whakamārama: Ko te tuarā o te wharepuni te tāhuhu.
Scope Note: The ridgepole of the meeting house which extends from the back of the house to the porch in front.
Whakamārama: Te kore (o te tinana) i tino ora, te noho hē i te pāngia e tētahi āhuatanga kino.
Scope Note: A general heading covering medical conditions, diseases and disorders e.g. cancer, diabetes ; and disorders, e.g. autism. Use narrower terms if available.
Whakamārama: He momo rākau nā Tū. He rākau roa, he whāiti te rau, ka kāwitiwiti ki te arero. He huruhuru kurī, huruhuru manu rānei te tauri kei te arero.
Scope Note: A fighting staff with one end shaped like an arero/tongue, and the other as a blade. The arero end is often ornamented with a tauri/woven band of feathers or dog hair.
Scope Note: The world and its environment.

Scope Note: Estuarine or littoral coastal waters, as defined in Part IX of the Fisheries Act 1992, of special customary significance to iwi and hapū either as a source of food or for spiritual or cultural reasons, in recognition of rangatiratanga and fisheries rights secured by Article II of the Treaty of Waitangi. Managed by a committee made up of Tāngata Whenua, recreational and commercial representatives who make recommendations to the Minister of Fisheries for any restrictions. Use for works about iwi and hapū fishing activity in Taiapure areas. See also: Mātaitai (Fishing areas (Non-commercial)).
Whakamārama: Ngā wāhanga ai o te tinana, tae atu ki ngā wāhanga e whakatōkia ai he uri, pērā i te tara, i te wharekano, i te ure me ngā raho.

Scope Note: A migratory seabird with blue and yellow bill and black/brown plumage. Procellaria parkinsoni.
Whakamārama: Te reanga, tētahi hunga rānei kua wahine, kua tangata, engari kāore anō kia pakeke rawa.
Scope Note: Youth, teenagers, adolescents, 12-16. See also: Tamariki (Children, aged 5-12) and Taitamariki (Youth, teenagers, adolescents, about 16-21).
Whakamārama: Kei ngā tahataha o te raurau tēnei momo tā moko.
