Whakamārama: Ko te taitamariki, ko ngā tama wāhine, ngā tama tāne kua pakeke haere.
Scope Note: Youth, teenagers, adolescents, about 16-21. See also: Taiohi (Youth, teenagers, adolescents, 12-16) and Pakeke (Adults).
Whakamārama: Ka tāpiri atu ēnei tā moko ki te taiohou me te raurau.
Scope Note: This section of tattoos is in the angle of the jaw, bounded by the taiohou and raurau.
Whakamārama: Ko te kahokaho ka tuia atu ki te hononga o te rauawa me te kaunoti.
Scope Note: A batten on the outside of a waka/canoe to cover the join between the hull and the rauawa.
Whakamārama: He manu nō te ngahere, kaore e rere. Kei Te Whakataka-Kārehu-a-Tamatea anake. He rite, he nui ake i te pūkeko.

Scope Note: A large heavy-bodied flightless rail resembling the pūkeko/swamp hen. In the wild it is now found only in Fiordland. The North Island subspecies is extinct. Porphyrio mantelli hochstetteri.
Whakamārama: Ma te waewae e takahi ana kia ngāwari te hari te taki hoki i ngā mahi haka.
Scope Note: The rhythmical stamping of the foot to keep timing in Māori action songs.
Whakamārama: He manu moana, he parauri te tuarā, he mā te puku. He mā anō te mata, ā, he tohu pango kei te karapoti i ana karu.
Scope Note: A seabird with the plumage dark brown above and white underparts. The face is also white, with a dark mark around the eye. Pelagodroma marina.
Whakamārama: He momo toroa, he koikoi ngā ngutu, he ōrangi ngā karu. He mā ngā huruhuru, ko ngā pito o ngā parirau he pango, he hāurakaho te tipuaki me te porongāua.
Scope Note: A large seabird with white feathers, black-tipped wings and a sharp pointed bill. Its eyes are blue and the crown and nape are a light yellow/brown. Morus serrator.
Whakamārama: Ki te tākaro tētahi, ka whāia ngā mahi whakangahau me ngā mahi hākinakina.
Scope Note: A general term for all kinds of recreational activities.
Whakamārama: Ko te hua o te kawakawa.
Scope Note: Orange/red berry fruit of the kawakawa/pepper tree.
Whakamārama: Ko te tāke e tāpiri ana e te kāwanatanga ki te utu mo ngā mea hoko e te tangata.
Scope Note: The New Zealand tax for goods and services
Whakamārama: Ko ngā rākau whakapae i te kaiwae o te waka.
Scope Note: The cross-supports for the deck of a waka/canoe.
Whakamārama: Hei awhi tēnei momo koha i te iwi engari, ka whakahoki anō te whakaaro pēnei.
Scope Note: A conditional gift not to be mistaken for a "tuku", a gift to be looked after but not owned.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā whenua kei te taha moana, ko te ākau, ko te tāhuna.
Scope Note: A general term for seashores of all types.
Scope Note: A type of incantation.
Whakamārama: Koia nei te ingoa o te rā.
Scope Note: Traditional name for the sun; personification of the sun.
Whakamārama: Te tamaiti e pūhou tonu ana.
Scope Note: Children, aged 5-12. See also: Kōhungahunga (Pre-schoolers, aged 3-5) and Taiohi (Youth, teenagers, aged 12-16).
Whakamārama: He tamaiti i ōna tau tuatahi ki tēnei ao e ako ana ki te hīkoi.
Scope Note: Young children, or toddlers, aged between 12 and 18 months who are at the age of learning to walk. See also: Pēpē (Babies); Kōhungahunga (Pre-schoolers).

Whakamārama: He ika tai e 30-50 henemita te tipu, he māwhero, he kōura, he whero rānei te tinana, he kōtingotingo kahurangi anō kei te tinana, tekau mā rua ngā tara o te urutira, he ūpoko pūhuki. Pagrus auratus.
Scope Note: A coastal fish, growing to 30-50 cm long, with a pink, gold or red body that is speckled with blue, a 12-pointed dorsal fin, and a blunt head. Pagrus auratus.
Scope Note: The origin of the haka.
Whakamārama: I tēnei āhuatanga, ko Tāne te atua a te oranga o te tangata.
Scope Note: Tāne, the giver of life and good health.
Whakamārama: He rākau rite ki te toatoa. He rite ki te huruhuru whenua ngā raurau. Ko ngā hua he itiiti, he pūhui te tupu.
Scope Note: A tree with fernlike pointed leaves. The fruit is a cluster of small cones. Phyllocladus trichomanoides.
Whakamārama: He tama ō Ranginui rāua ko Papatūānuku. Ko ia te atua mo te tangata, mo ngā ngāherehere, mo ngā manu, mo ngā ngāngara, mo ngā ngārara me ngā kararehe.
Scope Note: The personification of forests, their human inhabitants, plants, insects and animals.
Whakamārama: Ko ia te kaitiaki o tēnei taonga pūoro, te rōria. E ōrite ana te rōria ki te Jews harp.
Scope Note: The guardian of the musical instrument rōria, which is similar to the Jews harp.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā taonga whakatangitangi i ahu mai i ngā tangi o ngā ngārara, o ngā ngāngara, o ngā manu, o ngā wai, o ngā rākau me ngā hau o te taiao.
Scope Note: These are instruments which imitate voices of the environment, e.g. insects, lizards, birds, waterways, rain, trees and winds.
Whakamārama: Ko te atua o te moana.
Scope Note: The god of the sea and all things living in it.
Whakamārama: Ko te tangata - he tangata takitahi. Tāpiria tēnei ūpoko ki ngā rekoata e pā ana ki ngā momo tuakiri o te iwi whānui, puta noa i Aotearoa. Tirohia anō hoki te rārangi e whai ake nei.
Scope Note: Persons or people of Aotearoa. Use this term as a broad category for the different social identities within Aotearoa. Use a narrower term instead where appropriate.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā pūrākau, ngā kōrero tuku iho, ngā kōrero tūturu hoki e pā ana ki ngā mana, ki ngā reo nō ngā moutere o Te Moana-nui-a-Kiwa.
Scope Note: Pacific Island nations and culture.
Whakamārama: Ko te iwi taketake o Aotearoa, ko te Māori, nō rātou te whenua.
Scope Note: Describes the Māori people, who are the indigenous people of New Zealand, as a collective. See also Iwi taketake (Indigenous peoples and cultures).
Whakamārama: Ko ngā ritenga e pā ana ki te tūpapaku ā, tae noa ki te nehunga.
Scope Note: The mourning ceremonies and rituals preceding and including a funeral.
Whakamārama: Koia nei ngā whakairo o ngā mahi whatu.
Scope Note: A form of finger weaving creating geometric patterns used to decorate garments such as cloaks, belts and anklets.
Whakamārama: He hanga weriweri, he hanga whakamataku, he kai tangata, he wā anō e noho kaitiaki ai, he wai hōhonu tōna kāinga.

Scope Note: Water spirits, creatures, chiefs, something or someone awesome who take many forms from logs to reptiles and whales and often live in lakes, rivers or the sea. They are often regarded as guardians by the people who live in their territory.
Whakamārama: Kei ia kokonga o te wharepuni me te mahau hoki he wāhi mo ngā whakairo taniwha.
Scope Note: Carvings located at each corner inside the meeting house and at each corner of the porch.
Whakamārama: He mea e kaingākautia ana, he nui rānei te utu, kāore rānei e tino kitea.
Scope Note: Something highly prized, or invaluable.
Whakamārama: Ngā taonga whakatangitangi tawhito a te Māori.
Scope Note: Traditional Māori musical instruments.
Whakamārama: Mā ngā rauemi e pā ana ki ngā taonga whakatangitangi.
Whakamārama: He tao tēnei ki te hopu ika.
Scope Note: A single pointed spear used for catching fish in shallow waters.
Whakamārama: Ko te tamāhine mātāmua o te aho ariki. Ka tiakina rawa kia noho tapu.
Scope Note: Firstborn women of families of rank, who were invested with special tapu.
Whakamārama: He momo otaota pirinoa, he ririki. He kāriki ngā pua, he hāpiapia, he māwhero ngā hua.
Scope Note: A mistletoe with sticky pink fruits and small green flowers. Tupeia antarctica.
Whakamārama: He ritenga whakawehe i te tangata, i te taonga i tētahi āhua rānei, kia kaua e whāwhāria, e takahia, ā, kia tūpato te haere.
Scope Note: A status of separateness conferred by ritual to set things apart from ordinary matters (noa). When under tapu things were forbidden or treated differently from things noa.
Whakamārama: He hanga, he mihini, he aha atu rānei e rite ana mō tētahi mahi.
Scope Note: Gear, equipment, goods, property, apparatus, utensils, hardware, gadgets.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā taputapu hei ahu i ngā māra.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā rawa, ko ngā taonga hoki ka whakamahia ai te kohi kaimoana, te hī ika rānei.
Scope Note: All fishing tools, equipment and implements.
Whakamārama: He manu moana. He tāhei mā kei ngā ngutu. He hinatea ngā parirau, he pango ngā waewae me te tipuaki, ā, he mā te kakī, me te poho.
Scope Note: The most common tern. The wings are pale grey, the feet and cap are black and the neck and breast are white. There is a white band just above the bill. Sterna striata.
Whakamārama: He rākau tūraha, torotika tonu te tīwai. He whānui, he porotaka ngā rau. He rarahi, he porouri ngā hua, he rite ki o te tawa.
Scope Note: A spreading tree with a straight trunk. It has broad rounded leaves and purple fruit like that of the tawa. Beilschmiedia tarairi.
Whakamārama: He mauwha pūioio. He whāiti ngā rau, he whīwhiwhi ngā tātā.
Scope Note: A tough shrub of sandy places with small narrow leaves and entangled stems. Coprosma acerosa.
Whakamārama: He otaota wekuweku. He taratara ngā tawhera, he takotako, he taratara anō ngā pūhui pua.
Scope Note: A tufted plant with sharp-spined compound leaves and an erect spiny flower head. Aciphylla spp.

Whakamārama: He manu tai, he mā a runga, he mā a raro, he pango te toi o ngā parirau kiwikiwi, he ngutu whero, he wae huirapa whero, he karu whero. Ko ngā momo ingoa rerekē mō te tarāpunga ko te akiaki, te hakorā, te karehākoa, te katatē, te manakorā, te taketake me te tarāpua hoki.

Scope Note: The most common seagull that has a white body with grey wings, and red eyes, beak and legs. Larus novaehollandiae scopulinus. See also: Karoro (Black-backed Seagulls), Manu moana (Sea birds), Tara (White-fronted terns) and Kuaka (Eastern bar-tailed godwits).
Whakamārama: He rākau rite ki te haekaro. He pūngarungaru, he kakara ngā rau, he kōwhai ngā pua. Penupenua ai ngā rau ki te pia hei whakakakara.
Scope Note: A tree with crinkly fragrant leaves and yellow flowers. The leaves and gum were used in making scents. Pittosporum eugenioides.
Whakamārama: He momo whakairo tēnei, he toro piko haere ana te āhua.
Scope Note: A knotched zig-zag set of carvings.
Whakamārama: Tēnei te wāhi e wātea ana mo ngā ope tūārangi, moe ai kei te taha matau o te tatau i rō whare te tarawharanui.
Scope Note: The space located at the right inside the meeting house.
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tū. He pakini te tara kia whati ai.
Scope Note: A spear or dart with a notched point used as a weapon.
Scope Note: Venus as a morning star.
Whakamārama: He hua whenua i heria mai i Hawaiiki. He rarahi ngā rau, ko te pūtake he tino kai nā ngā iwi katoa o ngā moutere o Te Moana nui-a-Kiwa.
Scope Note: Introduced by Māori for the edible rootstock. Now an important vegetable for Polynesian communities. Colocasia esculenta.
Scope Note: Wicker trap for catching crayfish.
Scope Note: Weeds or any small vegetation.
Whakamārama: Te putanga o te whakapapa.
Whakamārama: Te āta tirohia i ngā mahi o ngā whetū.
Scope Note: Science of the heavens; the study of heavenly bodies.
Whakamārama: He kahui whetū, pērā i a Matariki.
Scope Note: A group of fixed stars, e.g. Matariki/Pleiades.
Whakamārama: Te tirohanga me te āta whakāmarama o te kauhau, kōrerorero, tuhinga rānei.
Scope Note: The detailed examination of a lecture, speech or written account.
Whakamārama: He ingoa tūturu te tatau mo te kuwaha.
Scope Note: The door of the meeting house.
Whakamārama: He kirimana maungārongo me te whakawhiti taonga rānei te tikanga o te tatau pounamu.
Scope Note: Peace agreements, including the exchanging of gifts and often marriage.
Whakamārama: Te kaute o ngā tāngata e noho mai ana ki tēnā wāhi, ki tēnā wāhi.
Scope Note: The characteristics of people living in a certain area.
Whakamārama: He momo taura e mau ana i te maro.
Scope Note: A type of belt to hold an apron.
Whakamārama: Ko te hokowhitu toa e whakatika ana ki te pakanga.
Scope Note: A fighting force of Māori.
Whakamārama: He ope taua ka haere ki te muru i ngā taonga a te hunga hara ki ā rātou.
Scope Note: An institutionalised form of violent fighting as a means of settling disputes. The offender was stripped of property by the plundering party.
Whakamārama: He mauwha kaho, pūhuruhuru. Āhua rite ki te koromiko. Kei te kāmata rawa ngā pūhui pua.
Scope Note: A shrub covered with yellowish tomentum, with the appearance of a small leaved koromiko/hebe. The flower clusters are at the tips of the branchlets. Cassinia leptophylla.
Whakamārama: He manu ririki, kāriki. He mā te porowhita kei ngā karu. Nāna anō ia i kawe mai i Ahitereia.
Scope Note: A small green bird with a white circle around the eyes, self-introduced from Australia. Zosterops lateralis.
Whakamārama: Ko te tekoteko whakairo o te ihu o te waka taua.
Scope Note: A carved figure mounted on the bow of a waka taua/war canoe.
Whakamārama: He tauira te akonga e whai atu ana i ngā mātauranga katoa o tētahi tohunga nōna anake tōna ake mātauranga.
Scope Note: A pupil under instruction and tutelage in a specific branch of knowledge.
Whakamārama: He momo tautohetohe engari ēhara a tētahi e aro atu ki tētahi atu.
Scope Note: A debating process where both sides cannot come to a general agreement.
Whakamārama: Ka whakataetae mō tētahi mea i runga i te ngākau pai.
Scope Note: Competitive activities with a recreational or social focus. See also: Competitive activities
Whakamārama: Ka tohua hei hoa rangatira mō tētahi atu ā tōna wā.
Scope Note: A cultural practice where marriage is formally arranged by the grandfathers of the two communities to which the prospective bride and groom belong.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā kōrero e pā ana ki ngā ingoa Māori o ngā momo wāhi katoa.
Scope Note: Use for works about meanings and origins of placenames and landmarks. See also Ingoa (Personal names).
Whakamārama: He wāhi hī ika no te hau kāinga taua wāhi.
Scope Note: A familiar fishing spot of the local Māori.
Whakamārama: He karakia mo te waka. Kia tau ai te tauparapara i te whaikōrero.
Scope Note: Chanting of prayers for waka/canoes, or, compositions recited to introduce and move forward a formal speech.
Whakamārama: E tata rawa atu e ngā tāngata tautohetohe ana ki te whawhai, patu rānei.
Scope Note: To beat one another, a physical argument.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo taura katoa.
Scope Note: A general term for ropes, cables and cords.
Whakamārama: Ko te taura here i te punga o te waka.
Scope Note: Anchor rope of waka/canoes.
Whakamārama: Ko te wāhi e tau ai te waka, ka kūmea ki uta.
Scope Note: Landing places where waka/canoes were drawn up out of the water.
Whakamārama: Ko te pou whakairo, whakahirahira o te kei o te waka taua.
Scope Note: The carved sternpost of a waka taua/war canoe.
Whakamārama: He rākau roa, torotika. He whāiti, he koikoi ngā rau. He pūkaka, he taitea, hei tao huia. He rarahi, he poropango ngā hua, kainga ai. Mahia ai he rongoa ki ngā rau.

Scope Note: A tall erect tree with narrow pointed leaves and large blackish stone-fruits which were used for food. The wood is pale and straight grained but soft and was used for bird spears. An important medicinal plant. Beilschmiedia tawa.
Whakamārama: He rākau kei te takutai moana o Te Tai Tokerau. Ka rere te tawau mehemea ka tapahia. Ko ngā hua he nunui, he whero. Ko ngā kākano he nunui, tuia ai hei taonga mau kakī.

Scope Note: A coastal tree of the north of the North Island. The tree bleeds a milky sap when cut. The berry is large and turns red. The seeds are large and were formerly used for making necklaces. Planchonella costata.
Whakamārama: Rākau kei te ngāhere kei ngā maunga e tupu ana. Ko ngā rau, he whāiti, he nihoniho ngā tapa. He kārikitea ngā pua, he whākou rā.
Scope Note: A tree of mountain forests with distinctive narrow leaves with blunt teeth and large cream/green flowers called whākou. Ixerba brexioides.
Whakamārama: He ika matatuhi, rarahi ngā karu. He hanga rite ki te kahawai pūhihi. He ōrangi kāriki te tuarā, he mā kākonu te poho me ngā tohu kerekere rite ki te moko.

Scope Note: A shoaling fish shaped like a slender kahawai with a large eye. The ground colour is blue/green above and silvery white below, with an irregular pattern of dark markings like a moko above. Scomber australasicus.
Whakamārama: He rākau roa, he rākau pāpua, nō te ngahere. He ririki, he porotaka he nihoniho ngā rau, he tauhokohoko te tipu.
Scope Note: A tall forest tree with spreading branches. The small, rounded, toothed leaves alternate in two rows. Nothofagus menziesii.
Whakamārama: He momo tāwhai, he ririki, he matahua ngā rau, he hinauri te tīwai.
Scope Note: A beech with small oval leaves and a dark grey trunk. Nothofagus solandri.
Whakamārama: He momo tāwhai, he rarahi, he niniho ngā rau. He puwhero ngā raurau pūhouhou i te takurua.
Scope Note: A beech with rather large toothed leaves. The young foliage is tinted red in winter. Nothofagus fusca.
Whakamārama: He momo atua a Tāwhaki.
Whakamārama: He rākau kei te ngāhere kei ngā maunga e tupu ana. Ko ngā rau, he whāiti, he nihoniho ngā tapa. He kārikitea ngā pua, he whāhou rā.
Scope Note: A tree of mountain forests with distinctive narrow leaves with blunt teeth and large cream/green flowers called whākou. Ixerba brexioides.
Scope Note: The god of winds and weather.
Scope Note: Contemporary times, post-European times, after contact with Europeans.
Scope Note: Pre-European times, before contact with Europeans.
Te mahana haere o te ao
Mahana haere o te ao, Te
Te Pakanga Tuatahi o Te Ao
Pakanga Tuatahi o Te Ao, Te
Whakamārama: Ko te whanaungatanga o ngā mea katoa i roto i te ngahere.
Scope Note: Covering all aspects of forest ecology.
Whakamārama: Te Matau a Māui. Ko Matariki rātou ko Kōkota, ko Sirius, ko Atutahi, ko Tautoru te whānau whetu o Te Waka o Tama-rereti. Kei tua atu i tēnei whānau ko Te Matau a Māui.

Scope Note: A combination of star constellations including Matariki/Pleaides, Kōkota/Hyades, Sirius/Takurua, Atutahi/Canopus and Orion's Belt/Tautoru to form a waka shape known as Te Waka o Tama-rereti. The constellation only appears opposite Scorpio/ Te Matau a Māui.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā rākau katoa, ahakoa he kauri, he horopito, he otaota, he putiputi hoki.
Scope Note: All land plants including trees, shrubs, grasses and flowers.
Whakamārama: Ko te nuinga o ngā tekoteko, he whakairo noa o te tūpuna nōna te hapū. Kei runga i te tuanui i mua o te wharepuni.
Scope Note: This represents the ancestor for whom the carved meeting house is named.
Whakamārama: He momo tao, he potopoto, he koikoi, hei paoka i te hoariri.
Scope Note: A short stabbing spear used in hand-to-hand fighting.
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tū. He koikoi tētahi pito, he āhua rite ki te toki te rau.
Scope Note: A fighting staff of wood with one end pointed and the other expanded into a broad blade on one side.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo tī katoa. Tirohia ngā momo tī i te rārangi kupu whāiti.
Scope Note: A general term for the different kinds of cabbage trees, species of Cordyline.
Whakamārama: He momo tī ririki, he rite ki te wharariki.
Scope Note: A small grasslike relative of the cabbage tree. Cordyline pumilio.
Whakamārama: He rākau tupu noa iho. He rite ngā rau ki o te kiekie, engari he poto iho.
Scope Note: The common large kind of cabbage tree. Cordyline australis.
Whakamārama: He momo tī, kei ngā tapa o te ngahere e tupu ana. He whāiti te tīwai, he roroa ngā rau, he kupakupa ngā pūhui pua.
Scope Note: A type of cabbage tree often found in forest margins, with a narrow stem, long leaves and a loose flowerstalk. Cordyline banksii.
Whakamārama: He momo tī i heria mai i Hawaiiki.
Scope Note: A naturalised Polynesian tree with ornamental cultivars, originally introduced by Māori. Cordyline terminalis.
Whakamārama: He rākau, āhua kotahi mita te roa hei whakapakari i te tinana; ki te whakakoi i te hinengaro; ki te takaro hoki.
Scope Note: Stick games, usually played in pairs, using medium length sticks (approx. 1 metre). See also Tītī tōrea using short sticks.
Whakamārama: He momo tī, kei ngā ngahere o ngā maunga e tupu ana. He whānui ake ngā rau i o ētahi atu momo tī.
Scope Note: A cabbage tree of mountain forests with broader leaves than the common type (Cordyline australis). Cordyline indivisa.
Whakamārama: Ko te tiakitanga te awhi, me te manaaki o te whenua o te tangata.
Scope Note: Caring for land and people.
Whakamārama: He manu nō ngā ngahere. He pango ngā huruhuru, he ura ngā pokohiwi me te tuarā.
Scope Note: A rare forest bird. The feathers are black except for the shoulders and back, which are reddish brown. Philesturnus carunculatus.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tikanga katoa a te Māori. Āta tirohia te āhuatanga e rite ana. Kua whānui rawa hoki te rere o ēnei kōrero i ēnei ra.

Scope Note: The correct and true way; customs and traditions that have been handed down through time. Use as an additional subject heading when any ritual or process, connected with a topic, is being described, e.g. welcomes, funerals, canoe traditions, war, education, arts.
Whakamārama: He rerekē ngā tikanga a tēnā iwi, a tēnā iwi.
Scope Note: The customs and traditions particular to individual iwi.
Whakamārama: Ka āhei te tangata kia whakamārama ai, ā, kia tū tōtika ai i roto i ngā ao e rua e tino rerekē ana.
Scope Note: The ability to understand and function effectively in two distinct cultural paradigms or environments.
Whakamārama: Ngā tika, ngā mana o te tangata.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tikanga Māori e pā ana ki te wairua, ki te hinengaro o te tangata.
Scope Note: Abstract values and principles which underlie Māori social relations and correct conduct.
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tū, he taumaha, he koikoi, kei tētahi pito he kou.
Scope Note: A bludgeon-like weapon with a heavy pointed knob on one side.

Whakamārama: He rerenga kōrero i kapohia atu i te pukapuka o te tau 1835.'He wakaputanga o te Rangatiratanga o Nu Tireni' mo 'ngā tino Rangatira kia mau te mana o tēnei whenua ki a rātou'. Ka ara ake ano o Te Tiriti o Waitangi. Taka rawa mai ki te tekau tau mai i 1990, kua huaina hei whakaata i te mana Māori Motuhake hei whakahaere i te iwi, hāunga ake te kāwanatanga.
Scope Note: Traditional usage: paramount chieftaincy. Contemporary usage: the autonomy of Māori to determine their own affairs, independent of government.
Whakamārama: He kai moana, he torehapehape te anga. Ko te tio para, ko te tio reperepe.
Scope Note: A general term for oysters.
Whakamārama: He kai moana. He haupapa tētahi o ngā anga, he kōkohu tētahi.
Scope Note: A general term for scallops.
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tū, he momo patu. Kia tata tonu mai te hoariri, ka whiua atu.
Scope Note: A short club used as a weapon, thrown by hand at close range.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti, kei ngā wāhi katoa. He kōkirikiri, he kōtiutiu te rere, he kaikai ngārara. He pango te tinana, ko te remu he kōheuheu te hanga, he tauhokohoko he mā he pango.
Scope Note: A common darting bird which feeds on insects. It is easily identified by its white and black fan shaped tail. Rhipidura fuliginosa.
Whakamārama: He manu moana pērā i te ōi, he hāurahina. Whakaritea ai te wā mō te nanao tītī hei huahua, hei tuku rānei ki te wai kurutai.
Scope Note: Tītī is the South Island muttonbird. It is a brown grey shearwater resembling ōi/North Island muttonbird. Puffinus griseus.
Whakamārama: Ko te tā moko tēnei kei waenganui o te rae.
Scope Note: The tattoo design in the centre of the forehead.
Whakamārama: E rua ngā rākau, āhua 30cm te roa hei kīnaki mo te waiata, hei mahi whakapakari i te tinana, hei takaro hoki. I te nuinga o te wā, tokorua ngā kaitākaro e pūrei ana ki tēnei mahi.
Scope Note: Stick games, usually played in pairs, using short sticks (approx. 30cm). See also Tī rākau using medium length sticks.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti nō te moana. He rite ki te pararā, engari pango noa ake te kurutou. He maha ngā momo o tēnei manu.
Scope Note: A small seabird like the pararā/broad-billed prion but with more black on the tail. There are several races of this bird. Pachyptila turtur.
Whakamārama: He manu itiiti nō te ngahere, he rite ki te mātuhituhi engari ko te uma he mā. Ko te tipuaki me te tuarā o te tame he kāriki. Ko te uwha he hāura kōtiwhatiwha.
Scope Note: A very small wren of the forest, resembling the mātuhituhi/bush wren but with a white breast. The male is green on the cap and back, the female brownish. Acanthisitta chloris.
Whakamārama: He rākau nō te ngahere. He tāwhera ngā rau. Ko ngā hua he wherowhero. Ko te karihi he pango, i ōna rā ka taona, ka whakawiria kia taea te hinu.
Scope Note: A tree with compound leaves, most notable for the fruit which is a black seed, within a red fleshy covering, in a brown cup. Oil was extracted from the seeds. Alectryon excelsum.
Whakamārama: Ko te tītoko o te rā o te waka, hei pupuri i te rā ka wherahia ana.
Scope Note: The spreader (sprit) for a sail used on a waka/canoe.
Whakamārama: He āhua rite ki ngā hihi o te rā ēnei momo tā moko ki runga i ngā tukemata.
Scope Note: These are the ray-like tattoos above the eyebrows.
Scope Note: Includes sports people, people who overcome, people at the top of their fields.
Whakamārama: Ko te wāhi tō i ngā waka i te whenua. He motumotu tōroa te kaupapa.
Scope Note: Places where waka/canoes were dragged overland, portages.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo toetoe, whara rānei. He kōroaroa ngā rau, he kokoi ngā tapa.
Scope Note: A general term for large tussock-like grasses and sedges, especially those with sharp edges to the leaves.
Whakamārama: He toetoe rahi, he pā te tupu. Hei te timatanga o te raumati takotako te tū o te tātā pūhui.
Scope Note: A large tussock grass forming a clump with erect loose flower heads in early summer. Chionochloa conspicua subsp. cunninghamii.
Whakamārama: Ko te momo toetoe, rite ki te māpere. Ko ngā pūhui he roroa, he pango, he pūhuruhuru. He ura ngā pata.
Scope Note: A sedge with long, loose, black, hairy flowerheads. The nuts are red brown. Gahnia lacera.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo toetoe rarahi o te ngahere. He ratarata ngā tapa o ngā rau.
Scope Note: A general term for large cutty-grass type sedges with cutting edges to the leaves. They are common in forests. Gahnia spp.
Whakamārama: He momo toetoe, he wekuweku te tupu, he kaitara ngā rau. Kei ngā repo, kei ngā wāhi mākū e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A coarse leaved tufted sedge found in wet places. It is a troublesome pasture weed. Carex coriacea.
Whakamārama: He momo toetoe, kei te repo e tupu ana. Kia pakari, kua rīraparapa te tātā, hei kāhiwi poto noa nei.
Scope Note: A sedge with a long, loose flowerhead of small spikelets. It grows in swamps and often forms a short trunk made of matted roots and old leaves.

Whakamārama: He momo pipi, rarahi noa atu i te tuatua. He moeone i ngā onepū hōhonu. He tino kai, e rāhuitia ana. E toru noa ōna kāinga, kei Te Ara-a-Kiwa, kei te uru o Te Tai Tokerau, kei Horowhenua.

Scope Note: A large bivalve resembling the tuatua, living deeply buried in beach sands. It is a protected delicacy but is found only in Foveaux Strait, the Waikanae coast and on the west coast of Te Tai Tokerau. Paphies ventricosa.
Whakamārama: Ngā tini a Tangaroa ka kohia hei kai mā te tangata. Ki ētahi, ka whāiti mai te kupu nei ki ngā hanga piri toka, noho onepū, kāore e uru mai ngā ika tere i te moana nui tonu.
Scope Note: The multitudes of Tangaroa (foodstuffs) gathered by people to eat. To some, this word relates to shellfish found on rocks, in the sand, or marine life found inshore.
Whakamārama: He mea kitea, hei whakamana.
Scope Note: Signs, symbols, acknowledgements, and omens.
Whakamārama: Omens or signs of good fortune.
Scope Note: Ko ngā tohu o te waimarie.
Whakamārama: He tohu kua whakamātauria e te hunga whai mātauranga.
Scope Note: Academic qualifications, including NCEA, university degrees.
Whakamārama: He akonga o te wairua nui, he tangata mātatau, he pūkenga, he tangata karakia me ngā ritenga o te whare wānanga. Tēnā te mana me te tapu o te tohunga me tōna pūmanawa.
Scope Note: A student of the source and a master of impeccable skill and talent who has the ability to perform specific incantations and rites correctly and to teach others.
Whakamārama: He tohunga turanga teitei, nui tōna mana me tōna tapu.
Scope Note: An expert priest of the highest class.
Whakamārama: He tohunga e mātatau ana ki ngā mahi tuku kēhua.
Scope Note: An expert priest who has the ability to exorcise spirits from the living world to the spirit world.
Whakamārama: He tohunga mō te tātai arorangi.
Scope Note: An expert in star lore and traditional navigation by the stars.
Whakamārama: He tohunga e mātatau ana ki ngā mahi mākutu.
Scope Note: An expert sorcerer skilled in casting incantations or spells causing death.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tohunga e hōmai ana te māramatanga e te wāhi ngaro.
Scope Note: Priestly seers and skilled orators of prophecy. Commonly used to describe the Māori prophets of the 19th century e.g. Te Kooti, Papahurihia.
Whakamārama: He tohunga rongonui mo te tā moko.
Scope Note: An expert in the art of traditional tattooing.
Whakamārama: He tohunga mō ngā tikanga mahi whakairo.
Scope Note: An expert carver in the art of traditional carving.
Scope Note: Can be used for examples of directories or for works about directories.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā mahi toi katoa o te ao Māori.
Scope Note: A tattoed, preserved head of Māori or Moriori. The terms Mokomōkai and Mokamōkai refer only to the heads of slaves, although many of the Toi moko were not slave heads.

Scope Note: Contemporary Māori performing arts, including dance, drama and theatre performances. Includes performances on stage, radio, television and film. See the broader term Waka toi for all forms of contemporary Māori arts. See also: Reo irirangi (Radio), Pouaka whakaata (Television) and Kiriata (Film).
Whakamārama: Te kitenga me ngā rangahau kōrero o te ao kōhatu.
Scope Note: The study of rocks.
Whakamārama: He momo taonga pūoro te tōkere e rite ana ki te tumutumu engari he ngāwari tana reo, ā, i hanga mai i te rākau, kōiwi, anga rānei.
Scope Note: Similar to the tumutumu percussion instruments except that the sound of the tōkere is softer and it is made of either wood, bone or shells.
Whakamārama: He toki ahu whenua, he toki pakanga, he toki whakairo, he toki iriiri.
Scope Note: Different types of adzes used for gardening, carving, warfare and other ceremonial purposes
Whakamārama: Ko te mahi taurima a te kāwanatanga me ngā rōpū tautoko hei hāpai i te hauora a te tangata e noho rawakore nei.
Scope Note: Work undertaken by government and support groups striving to promote the basic well-being of people in need.
Scope Note: A company or band of persons.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā wētā itiiti, roroa ngā waewae me ngā pūhihi. Noho ai i ngā ana.
Scope Note: Long-legged weta, commonly called cave weta.
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tū, he rākau roa, he rākau māro, he tōtōkau.
Scope Note: A general term for long plain fighting staffs made of hard wood.
Whakamārama: Ko te pou o te rā o te waka.
Scope Note: The mast of a waka/canoe.

Whakamārama: Ko ngā kōrero o roto o Tainui, ko wā Tainui ka kī ake he tongi. Nā, he nui ngā tongi a Tāwhiao, ko te mea e mōhio whānuitia ana: "Kotahi anō te kōwhao o te ngira e kuhunga ai te miro mā, te miro whero, me te miro pango."

Scope Note: Tongi/quotations were associated with the people of Tainui, particularly to Tāwhiao. The most renowned of his tongi was: "There is but one eye of the needle through which the white, red and black threads can pass."
Whakamārama: Ko te tono he inoi kia whakaae mai ki te mahi i ngā mea e hiahiatia ana.
Scope Note: A type of karakia/prayer requesting/wishing for/pleading for something, with hope but no automatic expectation that the request will be fulfilled.
Whakamārama: He momo kākahu kurī, he pango, he mā ngā tāhekeheke.
Scope Note: A type of dogskin cloak of black and white stripes.
He Wakaputanga o te Rangatiratanga o Niu Tireni
Whakamārama: Te ranga e kumea ana e ngā iwi hei mau mana.
Scope Note: Process, methodology and distribution of power within society.
Whakamārama: He manu kautū, he pango, he mā ngā huruhuru. Ko ngā ngutu he roroa, he rahirahi, he wherowhero. He wherowhero anō hoki ngā karu, me ngā waewae.
Scope Note: A wading bird with black and white feathers and a long thin straight red bill, red eyes and red legs. Haematopus ostralegus.
Whakamārama: Ko tēnei tōrea he pango katoa ngā huruhuru, he wherowhero anō ngā ngutu, ngā karu me ngā waewae.
Scope Note: An oystercatcher which has entirely black feathers, with a red bill, red eyes and red legs. Haematopus unicolor.
Whakamārama: He mohio kupenga, he kete te āhua.
Scope Note: Trap net or small bag containing bait for fish.
Whakamārama: Ka riko te marama i muri iho i tōna kīnga te tōriwha.
Scope Note: The waning of the moon.
Whakamārama: He manu moana tino nui. Mā kātoa, engari he pango ngā topito o ngā parirau. Ko te Rae o Taiaroa, i Otepoti, te kāinga.

Scope Note: A very large albatross, almost completely white except for the wing tips. There are two subspecies, epomophora and sandfordi. It is the latter which breeds at Taiaroa Heads. Diomedea epomophora.
Whakamārama: He manu moana nui, he hāurahina uira te tinana, he parauri ake te ūpoko me te kurutou. He mā te tohu kei ngā rewha.
Scope Note: A large albatross with pearly brown plumage except for a white mark on the eyelid. The tail and head are darker brown. Phaeobetria palpebrata.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā kai kua toroī i te rongo, nō reira he kai.
Whakamārama: He tino rākau tēnei nō te Wao-a-Tāne, mō te hanga whare, hanga waka, mō ngā whakairo. He mātotoru he rarai te kiri, he whāiti, he koikoi ngā rau, he pūwhero a taikākā.
Scope Note: A valuable timber tree with thick stringy, furrowed bark and sharp pointed narrow leaves. Podocarpus totara.
Whakamārama: Ko tēnei momo tōtara, he angiangi, he pākarukaru noa te kiri pērā i tō te kōtukutuku. He tino rākau anō mō ngā mahi nunui.
Scope Note: A tree resembling tōtara but with thin flaky paperlike bark, resembling that of the kōtukutuku/tree fuchsia. An important timber tree. Podocarpus hallii.
Whakamārama: He manu nō te ngāhere. He ūpoko nui, he roroa ngā waewae, tūmatohi tonu te tū.
Scope Note: A forest dwelling bird with erect posture, long legs and a large head.
Whakamārama: He rākau ririki, he rite ki te kāmahi engari he itiiti iho ngā raū.
Scope Note: A small tree resembling kāmahi, with small white flowers in erect flower clusters, but with smaller leaves which are bluntly toothed. Weinmannia silvicola.
Whakamārama: He wāhi tapu mō ngā mahi o te tohunga.
Scope Note: A ceremonial site or altar used by tohunga/priests for divination, etc.
Whakamārama: Ngā āhuatanga motuhake e tohu ana ko wai te tangata, te huinga tāngata rānei.

Scope Note: People's conceptions and expressions of their individuality or group affiliations and how they view themselves both as people and in relation to other people, ideas and nature. Use for works relating to Māori and identity issues such as tribal identity, sexuality, multicultural identity, religion, gender identity and nationalism. See also Mana ake (Self awareness).
Whakamārama: Kei runga ake te tuanui hei whakaruruhau mo te wharepuni.
Scope Note: The roof of the meeting house.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā reo o ngā ngāngara me ngā manu i puta mai i ngā rau.
Scope Note: Leaves used as a form of instrument to imitate insects and birds.
Whakamārama: He ngārara rahi, kei ngā motu o waho. I ētahi wā noho tahi ai i te rua o te tītī.
Scope Note: A large nocturnal lizard-like reptile found on offshore islands. Sphenodon punctatus.
Whakamārama: He pipi rite ki te toheroa, kei roto i te kirikiri e noho ana. He kaho, he kōataata te kiri o te anga.

Scope Note: A smaller relative of the toheroa, very common on east coast beaches where it lives shallowly buried. The hinge is closer to one end than to the other and there is a clear or yellowish epidermis. Paphies subtriangulata.

Whakamārama: Ko ngā tuhinga ōpaki katoa i ahu mai i te ngākau o te kaitito e whai wāhi atu ana i te rotarota, i te tuhi ā-whakaari, i te tito waiata, i te pakiwaitara, i te pūrākau, i te kōrero paki hoki.
Scope Note: Dramatic or creative expression conveyed through writing, including poetry, playwriting, screenwriting, songwriting, novels, epics, comedic writing, etc.
Kōrero paki mā te hunga taiohi
Kōrero pono mā te hunga taiohi
Whakamārama: Ko ngā kōrero ā-tuhi, pakiwaituhi katoa.
Scope Note: Fiction and non-fiction written works, including unpublished material, electronic literature, comic books and graphic novels. Use narrower terms where appropriate.
Scope Note: Use for writings by children.
Scope Note: Books, documents, etc., written by hand. This heading can be used for examples of manuscripts or for works about manuscripts.
Scope Note: Can be used for examples of theses or for works about theses.
Scope Note: Encompasses physical, online and intellectual exploration.
Whakamārama: He manu nui, he kārikipango mōhinuhinu, he mā ngā peruperu. Ko ngā waireka o ngā pua te kai.
Scope Note: A large nectar feeding bird with glossy green and black plumage and a tuft of white feathers at the throat. Prosthemadera novaeseelandiae.
Scope Note: See narrower terms for specific kinds of violence, e.g. child abuse, domestic violence.
Whakamārama: Ko te tūkinotanga ā te whenua, ā te moana, ā te taiao ranei.
Scope Note: The pollution of the environment.
Whakamārama: He otaota ririki, he rite ki te pārerarera.
Scope Note: A small plantain resembling pārerarera (a plantain variety).
Whakamārama: He tautoko ki ngā tāngata e hiahia āwhina ana.
Whakamārama: I riro whenua atu me hoki whenua mai.
Scope Note: Gifted land to be used for a particular time and then returned to the original owners.
Whakamārama: He mea whakahirahira te tukutuku e uhi ana i ngā pakitara o ngā whare tupuna.
Scope Note: Lattice work to adorn the walls of ancestral houses.
Whakamārama: Te kaitiaki o te pahū a Tūmatakōkiri. He ingoa anō mō Tūmatauenga.
Scope Note: The guardian of the drum, also known as Tūmatauenga, the god of war.
Whakamārama: Ko te atua o te whawhai, pakanga hoki ā Tūmatauenga.
Scope Note: The god of warfare.
Whakamārama: Ko te tumu kōrero, he pou kōrero o ngā kōrero e pā ana ki ngā rā ō mua.
Scope Note: Historians. See also Kōrero nehe (History).
Whakamārama: He momo taonga pao pao i te kōhatu, rākau me kōiwi.
Scope Note: Instruments of this type were percussion instruments using stone, wood and bone.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tuna waimāori, ngā tuna waitai.
Scope Note: Eels in general, both freshwater and saltwater.
Whakamārama: Ko te nohoanga mō te rangatira i te kei o te waka.
Scope Note: A platform in the stern of a waka/canoe, reserved for a person of rank.
Scope Note: Cooking methods and processes; to roast, broil, steam, cook, bake, etc.
Whakamārama: No te tini whāioio a Tūpai.
Scope Note: Tūpai is a sibling of the Sky father and Earth mother.
Whakamārama: He rākau, he kiriuka, he niniho ngā rau. He hāuratea ngā pūhui pua. He nehu kei ngā tātā.Kei ngā maunga e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A tree daisy with leathery, deeply-toothed leaves, branches appearing to be matted, and brownish flowerheads. It is found mostly in subalpine scrub. Olearia colensoi.
Whakamārama: He toetoe rahi rite tonu ki te toetoe tara ngārara.
Scope Note: A large erect sedge similar to toetoe tara ngarara. Gahnia xanthocarpa.
Whakamārama: Tētahi o ngā tangata i heke mai ai te tangata i roto i ngā tātai whakapapa, i tua atu i ōna mātua ake me ērā atu o tō rāua whakatupuranga.
Scope Note: Groups of people commonly referred to as ancestors of hapū and iwi. Can also apply to great-grandparents. See also: Kaumātua (Elders).
Whakamārama: Ko te tūrangawaewae mō te iwi nōna te whenua.
Scope Note: An ancestral area where a person has a sense of belonging or a "place to stand."
Whakamārama: Ko te ture te tikanga whakahaere.
Scope Note: Sports laws, including drug testing.
Scope Note: Criminal law, including homicide, theft and the Crimes Act 1961.
Scope Note: Company law, including entities and industrial relations.
Scope Note: Employment laws, including Employment Relations Act, human resources/paihere tangata, Human Rights Act, parental leave, Holidays Act.
Scope Note: Laws enacted by the Goverment, including public law, civil proceedings, legal systems, legal method, jurisprudence and repealed legislation/whakakorengia ture.
Scope Note: Environmental laws, including the Resource Management Act and Conservation Act, town planning and resource consents.
Scope Note: International environmental laws, including endangered species and whales.
Scope Note: Torts, including civil law, damages, deformation of character and negligence.
Scope Note: Equity and succession laws, including trusts and wills.
Scope Note: Family laws, including Guardianship Act and Domestic Violence Act.
Scope Note: Land laws, including the Land Transfer Act and Te Ture Whenua Māori Act.
Whakamārama: He rākau ririki. He ririki anō ngā rau, hahae ana ngā uaua. Ka tapahia te tūrepo, mātotoru ana te rere o te tāwau.
Scope Note: A small tree with small leaves conspicuously veined underneath. When the bark is cut it exudes thick white sap. The berry is red. Streblus heterophyllus.
Whakamārama: He oka hei wero i te hoariri.
Scope Note: A short stabbing spear used as a weapon.
Whakamārama: He mauwha, he rākau ririki, he tārewarewa ngā rārā, he mohinuhinu, he tauaro ngā rau. Ranea ana ngā pua me ngā kākano, heoi he haurua.
Scope Note: A shrub or small tree with drooping branchlets of glossy opposite leaves. The flowers and berries are profuse, but most parts of the plant are very poisonous. Coriaria arborea.
Whakamārama: He momo tutu ririki. Kei ngā wāhi mōheuheu kei ngā tahataha e tupu ana.
Scope Note: Small kinds of tutu found in subalpine country, including Coriaria angustissima, C. kingiana and C. plumosa. Coriaria spp.
Whakamārama: He momo para, pērā i te kāikaika. Hei te koanga ka pua, he kāriki, he māwhero ngā kawekawe.
Scope Note: A spring flowering terrestrial orchid with a green flower with trailing pink points to the sepals (leaf buds). Pterostylis banksii.
Whakamārama: He otaota tipu i roto i te wai. He pīrahirahi, he māwhero ngā tātā. He koikoi, he whāiti ngā rau. He pango ngā pata.
Scope Note: A water-dwelling plant with fragile pink stems, lanceolate (spearshaped) leaves and small pink buds. The seeds are black. Polygonum decipiens.
Whakamārama: He manu rite ki te pohowera engari he mangu te mata, he whero ngā karu, me ngā waewae. Ko ngā ngutu he pango, he whero.
Scope Note: A bird resembling the pohowera/banded dotterel but with a black face, red eye, red legs and a black and red bill. Thinornis novaeseelandiae.
Whakamārama: Nā Uenuku ngā tae o te kōpere.
Scope Note: The personification of the colours of the rainbow.
Whakamārama: He tūturu te tā moko ki tā te tangata hiahia, ōtira momo toi te mahi uhi mataora.
Scope Note: The applied art form of traditional Māori tattoos.
Scope Note: Traditional usage: the personification of lightning. Contemporary usage: flash of bright light produced by an electric discharge between clouds or cloud and ground.
Whakamārama: Kei ngā tahataha o te ihu, tata rawa hoki ēnei tā moko.
Scope Note: This section of facial tattoos is either side of the nose, to the edge of the eyes down to a line equal to the point of the nose.

Whakamārama: Ka rite tonu te pātai i tētahi atu, i ētahi atu i whiua ai e ngā kaipatapatai, pērā i te kaikawe kōrero, i te kairangahau, i te māngai o te kamupene, i te pirihimana, i a wai ake. Tāpiria tēnei kupu ki ngā rauemi e hāngai ana ki te mahi uiui me ngā uiuitanga.
Scope Note: Questioning or interviewing people or groups. Includes interviewing by journalists, by researchers, for jobs, by the police, etc. Can be used for interviews, or works about interviews.
Whakamārama: Kei tata rawa ki ngā taringa ēnei momo tā moko.
Scope Note: This area for the facial tattoo is from the temple to the centre of the ear on either side of the face.
Whakamārama: Te tirohanga o ngā mahi whakahaere.
Scope Note: The study of business, trade and commerce.
Whakamārama: He momo whakairo tēnei e ōrite ana tana āhua ki te kiri o te ika, pērā i te unahi.
Scope Note: A carving pattern which is likened to the scales of a fish, e.g. snapper.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā wāhi i ū ai ngā waka.
Scope Note: Landing sites for waka/canoes.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo pukapuka, wahanga rānei o te Paipera Tapu.
Scope Note: Use this term to describe collected books or a single book of the Bible, such as the book of Genesis, or the gospel of Luke.
Whakamārama: Ko te momo parāoa, rite ki te tahā te hanga o te ūpoko. Auau te pae ki ngā one mārakerake.
Scope Note: A medium-sized toothed whale with a bulbous head. It often strands in large numbers on exposed coasts. Globicephala melaena.
Whakamārama: He wāhi hei tanu i ngā tūpāpaku.
Scope Note: Land sites used for Māori burials.
Whakamārama: Ko te tikanga whakaea i te mahi kino, kōrero kino, mate kino. I ēnei wā, ko te moni e tukuna ana mō te hoko taonga, taputapu rānei, mō ngā mahi rānei.
Scope Note: A principle of Māori justice, involving just retribution for insult, ill-will, etc. In modern times also used in the sense of "price".
Whakamārama: He momo kai i hēria mai i Hawaiiki. Ka whakatōkia, ko te pūtake i kainga. Kua kore noa atu i whakatipuria.

Scope Note: The plant which produces yam tubers. Introduced by Māori, it has never naturalised and does not survive in the wild. Dioscorea sativa. The most common yam of commerce is probably D. alata.
Whakamārama: He tangata tirotiro haere noa ki te whenua. Ehara ia mō te noho hei tangata whenua.
Whakamārama: He momo karakia tēnei ki te tiaki i te tangata e karakia ana me tana iwi he waewae tapu i taua marae.
Scope Note: This is a type of prayer performed by a male as he and his tribesmen are entering a marae from outside of their tribal boundary.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo Aitanga Pēpeke pīrohea ngā tinana. Roroa, pēpeke ngā waewae.
Scope Note: Nematoceran flies with weak bodies and long legs, mostly associated with water.
Whakamārama: He mātukutuku tūtārere, he rite ngā rauhuru ki o te waewae kākā.
Scope Note: A wiry scrambling clubmoss. Lycopodium volubile.
Whakamārama: He rākau nā Tūmatauenga. I tāraia ki te rākau, ki te parāoa rānei. He rau tapatahi, he manaia te whakairo kei tētahi tapa.
Scope Note: A hand weapon of wood or bone, with only one side used as a blade, the other with a manaia (an image resembling a reptile with a birdlike head) carving.
Scope Note: Use also for bays, coves and harbours.
Whakamārama: Te tomokanga matua e kuhu ai, e puta ai te tangata i te marae, ētahi wā, i te urupā hoki.
Scope Note: Entrances to fortified pā, or more strictly, the main walk or roadway in the pā, marae or sometimes, burial grounds.
Whakamārama: Ka rahuitia a ētahi wāhi o te whenua pērā i ngā urupā, i ngā kāinga tāwhito o mua noa atu.
Scope Note: Land placed under permanent tapu/restriction such as urupā/burial grounds and places used for rites and ceremonies (not temporary bans or restrictions (rāhui)).
Whakamārama: Koia nei te kupu e rite ana mō ngā korero mō ngā wāhine Māori.
Scope Note: Use this term for material about Māori women.
Whakamārama: Ko te wahine tuatahi a te tangata punarua, maha rānei ngā wāhine.
Scope Note: The chief wife of a polygamous marriage.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā āhuatanga o te wai ki tā te Māori.
Whakamārama: He rongoa. Kōhuatia ai he take harakeke, ka inu i te wai. Te kawa ke!
Scope Note: A medicine made by boiling the roots of the flax, the liquid being drunk.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā wai reka o ngā pua rākau me ngā pua otaota.
Scope Note: A general term for nectars obtained from flowers and used as sweeteners.
Rātā o Te Ika a Māui
Whakamārama: Ko te wai honga o te rātā me ētahi atu rākau.
Scope Note: The nectar of the rātā and similar plants.
Whakamārama: Ko te wai honga o ngā pua o te harakeke.
Scope Note: The nectar of the flowers of harakeke/flax.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā wai o ngā awa, o ngā roto, o ngā puna, hei inu.
Scope Note: Freshwater of all kinds; drinkable water.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā wai tā moko me kōnatunatu te ngārahu ki te wai rākau.
Scope Note: A liquid pigment used in tattooing, made from sap mixed with soot.
Whakamārama: Ko te wai o ngā rākau hei mahi tae me ētahi atu mahi.
Scope Note: The sap of trees, which was used in foods, for the making of dyes and other purposes.
Whakamārama: Ko te wai totetote o te moana.
Scope Note: A term used to describe the sea, surf, or the tide and also used to distinguish sea water from fresh water.
Whakamārama: Mā te karakia e whakatapu. Hei whakaora tūroro, mō te tohi, mō te pure, mō te whakanoa me ērā āhua
Scope Note: Waters made tapu/sacred by karakia/prayers, having cultural and spiritual significance.
Whakamārama: Ko te wai o te māhoe, o te poroporo, o te tī, ka hanumi ki te ahowhare hei tae mō te moko.
Scope Note: Plant sap of māhoe, poroporo and tī, mixed with soot to produce wai ngarahu/pigment used for moko/tattoo patterns.
Whakamārama: He puna waiariki e hu ake ana i te whenua.
Scope Note: Geothermal hot springs in volcanic areas used for cooking, etc.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā waiata o te ao Māori, arā, he kupu whai rangi ka titoa, ka waiatatia e ngā kaiwaiata Māori.
Scope Note: All genres of Māori songs performed and/or composed by Māori artists. Includes contemporary Māori songs.
Scope Note: Songs expressing longing and love which may not be reciprocated.
Whakamārama: Ko te kaupapa o tēnei mahi he whakaako i a koutou ki te titiro ki ngā waiata i whakarērea mai e ō tātou koroua, kuia ki a tātou hei taonga mā tātou, ā, hei pupuri anō hoki mā tātou.
Scope Note: Traditional chants or songs treasured by all and handed down from Māori ancestors containing messages used to teach future generations.
Whakamārama: Ko te nuinga o ēnei momo waiata te putanga mai o ngā kōrero kikino, ngā kohukohu, ngā matenga, ngā whakatutuanga onamata.
Scope Note: Many of these types of songs were traditionally inspired by accidental death, murder or death in war. See also: Apakura (Dirges (Laments)).
Scope Note: A choral group performance.
Scope Note: Songs of instruction for future generations.
Whakamārama: He waiata e aroha atu ana a te wāhine ki a te tāne.
Scope Note: Songs of love addressed to a sweetheart.
Whakamārama: He pānui pukapuka, he mahi rorohiko ētahi tikanga ki te whakawaihangahia mātauranga.
Scope Note: Methods of disseminating knowledge.
Whakamārama: He momo tūroro o te hinengaro.
Scope Note: Temporarily deranged and mentally unstable.
Whakamārama: Ka mate te tangata, ka wehe te wairua, ka tomo ki te Ao Wairua.
Scope Note: Wairua are spirits. At a person's death the wairua is freed from the tinana/body and enters the Ao Wairua.
Whakamārama: Kei raro i ngā ngutu tēnei tā moko, engari kare i runga i te kauwae.
Scope Note: The facial tattoo pattern beneath the lower lip extending to the outer edge of the mouth rays.
Whakamārama: He momo otaota tawau, tupu ai i te takutai moana.
Scope Note: A plant with milky sap, usually found near the sea. Euphorbia glauca.

Whakamārama: He kahiwi rākau kua waimanutia, kia mānu ai i te mata o te wai, e haere ai ka hoea ki te hoe. He kupu whānui mō ngā mea ka āta hangaia hei kawe i te tangata, i te utanga, i te aha atu, ka haere i te moana, i te whenua, i te rangi rānei.

Scope Note: General term covering vessels or canoes of various types designed to carry things to a destination. This heading can apply to transportation and any mode of transport including vehicles, boats and airplanes, etc. Use a narrower term where appropriate.
Whakamārama: Ko waka he momo karangatanga hei whakakotahi i ētahi iwi.
Whakamārama: Ko te waka ama, he waka whāiti, kotahi te paepae hei kawe i ngā tāngata, kotahi anō kei te taha kia tika ai te tere i te wai.
Scope Note: Waka/canoes with an outrigger. See also: Ama.
Whakamārama: He waka e toru ngā wāhanga. Ka aukahatia kia kumi.
Scope Note: Plain waka/canoes made from three joined parts, the bow and stern lashed to the hull.
Whakamārama: E rua ngā kaunaroa o tēnei waka.
Whakamārama: He pouaka whakairo hei mau i ngā raukura huia. I ēnei wā ko te pouaka hei, he mea hei mau i ngā taonga pērā i te hei tiki.
Scope Note: Traditional usage: carved boxes for huia feathers. Contemporary usage: carved boxes for holding treasured items.
Whakamārama: He paepae wai, hei hopu kererū.
Scope Note: Water troughs set with noose, used to snare kererū and tūī.
Scope Note: Waka/canoes equipped with a sail.
Whakamārama: He momo waka, kei te titiro whakaroto te koneke.
Scope Note: Waka/canoes with figurehead facing inwards.
Whakamārama: He momo waka, i hāua i te rākau toitū.
Scope Note: Waka/canoes formed in a single piece rather than from joined sections.
Scope Note: Waka/canoes equipped with a sail.
Whakamārama: He momo waka kāore he rauawa.
Scope Note: Waka/canoes without raised sides ; river canoes made in one piece.
Whakamārama: Ahakoa e orite ana te āhuatanga o te waka tangata ki a te waka taua, kei te kawe te waka tangata i ngā tāngata katoa, tāne mai, wahine mai.
Scope Note: Although resembling a war canoe, the waka tangata carries people regardless of gender.
Whakamārama: He waka mō te ope taua. I tērā rau tau, ka huri te tikanga hei hari i ngā tangata hoa.
Scope Note: Richly carved large waka/canoes traditionally used by war parties ; ceremonial usage since early nineteenth century.
Whakamārama: He waka hao ika i te moana hui.
Scope Note: Ocean going waka/canoes used for fishing.
Whakamārama: He momo waka hei hī ika, hei hoehoe noa.
Scope Note: Plain waka/canoes used for fishing and everyday use.
Whakamārama: He momo waka kaore he rauawa.
Scope Note: Waka/canoes without raised sides.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā Mahi toi ka puta mai i te ao hou ki te ao tāwhito.
Scope Note: All forms of contemporary Māori art and/or revival of old traditions
Scope Note: A type of spaceship.
Whakamārama: He pouaka hei kawa kōiwi. He pouaka hei kawa tūpāpaku.
Scope Note: Traditional usage: carved chests used for human bones Contemporary usage: carved chests used for a deceased person.
Whakamārama: He paepae wai, hei hopu kererū.
Scope Note: Water troughs set with noose, used to snare kererū/wood pigeons and tūī.
Whakamārama: Ngā mātauranga, ngā mōhiotanga ki ngā karakia me ngā kōrero whai tikanga, whai mana o te iwi.
Scope Note: Learning through discussion to nurture and maintain traditional Māori knowledge, particularly at iwi and hapū level. For universities, see Whare wānanga

Whakamārama: Ko ngā Wātene Māori he momo rōpū tūao hei āwhina i ngā whānau, i ngā hapū, i ngā iwi me ngā tāngata katoa o te hapori. Ko tō rātou ake kaupapa, kia āta tiakina ngā hapori whānau e hui tōpū ai, e tae ana ki te mahi whakamarumaru, te whakahaere waka, me te āwhina turoro.

Scope Note: The Māori Wardens role is a voluntary initiative that provides a range of general services for the community including security, traffic control and first aid at large-scale community events.
Scope Note: A response of awe in reaction to ihi.
Whakamārama: He manu nō te ngahere, he ura ngā huruhuru. Tau ki te whenua, kaore e rere.
Scope Note: A flightless brown bird. Gallirallus australis.
Whakamārama: He ngārara, he roroa, he whāiti ngā tinana pērā i te peketua, i te matā rānei.
Scope Note: A category of ngārara/invertebrates including centipedes and earwigs.
Whakamārama: Ka tuma atu te kaitaki i tana taiaha te wero.
Scope Note: A challenge performed with the use of a traditional Māori weapon.
Whakamārama: He ngārara o te Aitanga Pepeke. He rite ki te pihareinga, he taumaha te tinana. Ko ngā momo Stenopelmatidae.
Scope Note: A general term for weta belonging to the family Stenopelmatidae.
Whakamārama: Te tuāhuatanga me te wetewetea i te reo.
Whakamārama: Mā ngā ringa ngā mahi o te whai.
Whakamārama: Ko te whai he ika moana, he papa, he whānui te tinana, he wero kei tōna whiore.
Scope Note: A sea fish with a flat broad body and a stinging tail.
Whakamārama: Ko te toi whakatakoto i te kupu kōrero, ā, me aua kōrero rā anō hoki.
Scope Note: The art of oration or rhetoric. Also used for an oration itself.
Whakamārama: Ko ia te āhua o te whaitiri.
Scope Note: Traditional usage: the personification of thunder. Contemporary usage: the loud noise heard after lightning and due to the disturbance of air by the discharge of electricity.
Whakamārama: Ki te whaiwhai koe i tētahi mea, ka kimi haere koe i taua mea kia mau i a koe.
Scope Note: Agreements, including oral, written and postal rule.
Whakamārama: Te āhua o tētahi mea kua peitahia, kua tāngia ki te pepa, ki te aha atu, kua hopukina rānei ki te kāmera.
Scope Note: A collective term covering contemporary images of the Māori world, including portraits, illustrations, drawings, graphics, paintings, photography, etc.
Whakamārama: He whakawhitinga o te ōhanga ā-motu, ōhanga ā-rohe hoki ki ngā ōhanga o te ao whānui.

Scope Note: The transition from national and regional economies to global economies. Can also apply to social, cultural and political aspects of globalisation. See also Āhuatanga pāpori (Social conditions).
Scope Note: Art exhibitions of images, excluding installations.
Whakamārama: Te urunga mai a te rōpu kapa haka ki runga it te atamira.
Scope Note: A song performed by the kapa haka group as it comes onto the stage.
Whakamārama: Te mahi whakahaere ā ngā kaimahi i āna mahi.
Scope Note: Managing staff in a workplace environment.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā whanonga hei whakaiti, hei aukati i te tangata nō tētahi atu iwi kē.
Scope Note: Discriminatory or abusive behaviour towards members of another race.
Whakamārama: Ka whakanikoniko i tētahi mea ki te tauira, ahakoa tuhi, ahakoa tārai ki te whao, ahakoa whatu, ahakoa tā ki te moko.
Scope Note: Any and all Māori patterns created as designs, whether drawn, carved with a chisel, woven, or applied as a moko.
Whakamārama: He momo hei, mau i te taringa me te kaki.
Scope Note: Jewellery worn as earrings and necklaces.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā āhuatanga o te mahi whakamāori me te whakawhiti reo.
Scope Note: Use for works about translations, translators or when bodies of work are translated into another language.
Scope Note: The study of the mind.
Whakamārama: Ka kōrerotia ake ngā take ā-hinengaro me ngā mahi a te hunga taiohi, 12-16 tau tō rātou pakeke.
Scope Note: Addresses the psychological issues and interests of adolescents, aged about 12-16.
Whakamārama: Ka kōrerotia ake ngā take ā-hinengaro me ngā mahi a te hunga taiohi, 16-21 tau tō rātou pakeke.
Scope Note: Addresses the psychological issues and interests of adolescents, aged about 16-21 years.
Whakamārama: Ka kōrerotia ake ngā take ā-hinengaro me ngā mahi a ngā tamariki, 5-12 tau tō rātou pakeke.
Scope Note: Addresses the psychological issues and interests of children, aged 5-12.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā mahi hei whakamana i ngā iwi, i ngā hapū, i ngā hapori whānau katoa.
Scope Note: Activities that increase positive outcomes within iwi, hapū and whānau communities by linking individuals and organisations working toward common ends.
Scope Note: The genealogical descent of all living things. Whakapapa/genealogy is a fundamental principle that permeates the whole of Māori culture.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo mahi me ngā rerekētanga o ngā hahi katoa o te ao.
Scope Note: A general term used to describe religious beliefs.
Scope Note: Traditional games and activities using sticks, hands and poi.
Whakamārama: Te tirohanga ā ngā kaimahi i āna mahi.
Scope Note: Measuring staff performance at work.
Whakamārama: Ka uru ki tētahi momo kakari, ki tētahi kaupapa rānei e tika ana kia puta he toa, me te whai kia toa ko koe.
Scope Note: Competitive activities with the focus on winning as the primary goal, including sports, speech competitions and political campaigns. See also: Competitive recreational activities
Scope Note: Competitive racing of waka/canoes at regattas.
Whakamārama: Whakataetae ā tau mo tetahi momo whaikōrero, kōrero hoki.
Scope Note: Annual secondary school speech competitions.
Whakamārama: He momo whakataetae, tautohetohe hoki mo ngā kura.
Scope Note: Speech competitions, e.g., for secondary schools.
Whakamārama: He rākau ririki nō Rēkohu. He kōwhaitea ngā pua. He karaka, he kura, he pango rānei ngā hua.
Scope Note: A yellow-flowered small tree from the Chatham Islands. The berry is orange or red to black. Corokia macrocarpa.
Scope Note: The placement of the body.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā tara ēnei e whakarakaitia ana i ngā tā e toropikopiko ana i ngā pāpāringa o te pane.
Scope Note: These are the spikes that decorate the large spirals on the facial tattoos.
Scope Note: Shorter form of welcome than a Powhiri.
Whakamārama: Ka whakatau te mauri o te hunga kua whakaparahako ai i ngā wā o mua, pērā i ngā whakahētanga i ahu mai ai i Te Tiriti o Waitangi.

Scope Note: Settlements which resonate with aggrieved groups in a deeper and more meaningful way. Use for matters relating to past grievances and Treaty of Waitangi settlements. See also : Kerēme (Tiriti o Waitangi), or, Whakatau take for general settlement issues.
Whakamārama: Ko te whakatau take, he whakataunga wenewene kia ea ai ngā tautohetohe, ngā pāmamae, ngā nawe o ētahi tangata, ētahi rōpū, ētahi whānau rānei.
Scope Note: A general term for disputes and settlements. Use for dispute resolution laws, including mediation, facilitation, group conferences and marae justice programmes.
Whakamārama: He momo whakataukī ēngari he kōrero ki tā te tangata kī.
Scope Note: Proverbs and traditional metaphorical sayings, said with emphasis. Sayings of a particular person or iwi/tribe.
Whakamārama: He kōrero tūturu mo tētahi wāhi, mahi, aha rānei ki tā te tangata, iwi rānei e tautoko ana.
Scope Note: Proverbs and traditional metaphorical sayings, said with emphasis. Sayings of unspecified origin.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā whakairo kei ngā tahataha o te tatau i te wharepuni.
Scope Note: The carved panels at either side of the meeting house door.
Whakamārama: He haka whakawātea i te atamira.
Scope Note: A song performed by the kapa haka group as it leaves the stage.
Scope Note: Includes physical, verbal and cyber bullying.
Scope Note: The skill of sharing information with each other.
Whakamārama: Te whanaketanga o te tangata.
Scope Note: The evolution of man and the world.
Whakamārama: Ko te whānau te pūtake o te hapū, iwi rānei.
Scope Note: The family is the natural and fundamental kinship unit of society.
Whakamārama: E marama ana te whānau mārama i te rangi, hei kākahu mo Ranginui.
Scope Note: Knowledge of all the heavenly bodies, e.g. sun, stars, etc.
Whakamārama: Te hononga ā-whakapapa, ā-toto, tētahi atu momo hononga rānei o te tangata ki tētahi atu e kīia ai he whanaunga, he hoa tata rānei.
Scope Note: A sense of belonging to a people; a system of kinship, including friendship and blood relationships between people.
Whakamārama: Ko te hunga e tipu ana ki raro i te maru o tana kuia, koroua, whānau ake rānei hi mea atawhai.
Scope Note: To take responsibility to feed, nurture and shelter a person, particularly a child.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā otaota whai rito pērā i te harakeke, i te kiekie, me ērā atu.
Scope Note: A category of plants with ensiform (sheathing) leaves, such as the harakeke/flax. Used for most monocotyledons (plants with a single seedleaf).
Whakamārama: Ko ngā momo whare katoa a te Māori. Tirohia i te kupu "Whare whakairo" ngā wāhanga o te whare.
Scope Note: A general term for all types of buildings, including dwellings, and storehouses. For terms for parts of carved whare see under "Whare whakairo".
Whakamārama: He nui tēnei whare hei hui i te iwi. He ruarua ngā whakairo.
Scope Note: A house with few carvings used generally for meetings.
Whakamārama: He whare hei kai mo ngā tāngata ki runga i te marae.
Scope Note: A dining room; eating house on the marae.
Whakamārama: He whare nohoanga mo te tūpāpaku. I te taha o te wharepuni te whare mate.
Scope Note: A small uncarved house adjacent to a meeting house where a dead body may lie for the duration of the funeral.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā wāhi kāinga te whare noho.
Scope Note: Dwellings or homes are termed housing.
Whakamārama: He nui rawa tēnei whare ā he ruarua noa iho ngā whakairo.
Scope Note: A large meeting house with very few carvings.
Whakamārama: He momo whare wananga mō te mahi raranga.
Whakamārama: Te whare āhuru mōwai o te pēpē e kukune mai ai i te kōpū o te whaea.
Scope Note: The house of human life, where new life is nurtured and developed in the womb.
Whakamārama: Ko te whare taonga he whare pupuri i ngā taonga o te ao whānui hei tirohanga mō te taonga.
Whakamārama: He whare whakairo te whare tūpuna.
Scope Note: An ornately carved meeting house named for an ancestor.
Whakamārama: He māhahau tēnei mo te noho waka.
Scope Note: A shelter to house waka/canoes.

Whakamārama: E rua ngā horopaki. Tuatahi, he whare, he wāhi rānei e whāngaia ai ngā tauira ki ngā āhuatanga o te kauwaerunga. Tuarua, he whare tuku mātauranga, mahi rangahau, kei a ia te mana ki te whakawhiwhi i ngā tohu mātauranga tino tiketike o te motu.

Scope Note: Houses of learning used in two different contexts. The first is traditional schools that teach pupils aspects of celestial knowledge. Second, is esteemed academic institutions that confer qualifications to graduates. See also: Wānanga (Traditional education) and Kura tuatoru (Tertiary education).
Whakamārama: Ngā momo wāhi e noho ai ngā kīrehe, ngā kararehe hoki ka whakaaturia atu ki ngā tangata.
Scope Note: Any area, building, cage, enclosure or other structure or premise in which a living animal or animals are kept for public exhibition or viewing.
Whakamārama: He whare e whakarei ana i ngā whakairo.
Scope Note: An ornately carved meeting house.
Whakamārama: He momo rākau rite ki te neinei, kei Te Wai Pounamu anake e tupu ana.
Scope Note: A tree resembling neinei (i.e. growing in forests in mountainous country with thin branches ending in a bunch of leaves), but found only in the South Island. Dracophyllum urvilleanum.
Whakamārama: He kura e kawe ana i ngā akoranga o te kura tuarua, ko te reo Māori te reo whakaako, e haere ai ngā ākonga o ngā kura kaupapa, o ngā akomanga rumaki rānei.

Scope Note: Secondary schools that teach students in the Māori language, designed for graduates of Kura Kaupapa Māori (Māori primary schools) and mainstream Māori immersion classes. See also Kura tuarua (Secondary schools (Mainstream)).
Whakamārama: He whare tūpuna e whakarei ana i ngā whakairo.
Scope Note: A carved meeting house, generally named for an ancestor.
Whāriki mo te papa i roto i te whare
Whakamārama: Ko ēnei ngā mea e hora nei i te papa ki rō wharepuni.
Scope Note: The woven mats which cover the floor of the meeting house
Whakamārama: He whāriki mo ia wahanga o te wharepuni, pērā i te mahau.
Scope Note: These are mats made for certain parts of the meeting house, such as those made specifically for the porch.
Whāriki mo te papa i roto i te whare
Whakamārama: He whāriki mo ia wahanga o te whare, pērā hoki te whāriki i rō whare.
Scope Note: These are mats made for specific parts of the house, like those used inside.
Scope Note: A type of tukutuku/lattice work design called 'double mouth'.
Whakamārama: He raranga katoa i te muka.
Scope Note: Whatu is a technique of twining to weave.
Whakamārama: He raranga ano te whatu kakahu.
Scope Note: A type of weaving mainly used for making clothes.
Whakamārama: He rākau tupu ai i te takutai moana. He rākau māā, pai hei kārewa. He nunui, he angiangi ngā rau. He maroke, he taratara ngā hua.
Scope Note: A coastal tree with very light wood used for fishing floats. The large thin leaves are heart-shaped. The fruit capsule is dry and spiny. Entelea arborescens.
Whakamārama: He momo ruru kua ngaro ki te ao. He rahi atu i te ruru koukou, he mā te mata.
Scope Note: A large extinct owl, bigger than the ruru/morepork and with a white face.
Whakamārama: He kaponga tupu noa. Ko ngā rauhuru he tūmārō, he pērā anō ngā tātā parauri. He āhua ura te tīwai, ā, e mau tonu ana ngā rauhuru maroke.
Scope Note: A common treefern with harsh fronds and a brownish trunk covered with the bases of dead fronds. The stalks are dark brown and tough to the touch. Dicksonia squarrosa.
Whakamārama: He kaponga rite ki te whekī. He weuweu hāuratea kei te take o te tīwai, pērā i o te mamaku. Ko ngā tātā he maene, he hāuratea.

Scope Note: A treefern with harsh fronds and brownish trunk resembling Whekī/rough treeferns, but with fine brown rootlets over the base of the trunk. The stalks of the fronds are pale brown and smooth. Dicksonia fibrosa.
Scope Note: A general term for lands of different types such as farmland, wasteland, swamps, reserves.
Whakamārama: Ka rere te whenua a muri i te putanga o te pēpe, katahi ka tukuna atu te whenua ki a Papatūānuku.
Scope Note: The placenta in afterbirth is traditionally taken back to the ancestral lands.
Whakamārama: He wāhi e watea ana i tetahi aituā, me te atawhai hoki i te whenua.
Scope Note: A temporary prohibition on the land against trespass in connection with tapu or to protect natural resources against overexploitation. Used commonly in the Department of Conservation.
Whakamārama: Raupatu o te taiaha. Raupatu o te kawanatanga.

Scope Note: Traditional usage: land in dispute. Contemporary usage: iwi/tribal lands confiscated by the government after the land wars. Used to describe content in the Waitangi Tribunal reports, Raupatu Bank Documents collection, Māori land law, Māori land history, New Zealand land law.
Whakamārama: He whenua e tautohetohe ana a Māori ma, a Māori me te Karauna hoki.
Scope Note: Lands of which the ownership is disputed/contested among Māori or between Māori and others e.g. the Crown. Used to describe content in the Waitangi Tribunal reports.
Whakamārama: He whenua tuku iho mai no tuawhakarere.
Scope Note: Entitlements to pass land down from one generation to another. Used commonly in Māori land courts and Māori land law.
Whakamārama: He rerekē ngā tikanga o ngā whetū ki ngā auahi tūroa. E ōrite ana ngā āhuatanga i ngā wā katoa.
Scope Note: Celestial bodies that have a regular pattern of rising and setting.
Whakamārama: Ko ngā whētu ēnei e amionga ana i te rā me te tāoronga i waenganui i ētahi atu o ngā whetu.
Scope Note: Heavenly bodies that orbit the sun and move among the stars.
Whakamārama: He pūkohu rārāpiri. He whiriwhiri ngā tātā, he porohita, he rite ki te ūnahi ngā rau.
Scope Note: A creeping moss which forms mats. The stems are plait-like with scale-like circular leaves. Lembophyllum divulsum.
Whakamārama: He rakiraki whakamokeke. He ōrangihina te tuarā, he kōpure ura. He hina te poho, he māwherotea ngā ngutu, he parauri ngā waewae.
Scope Note: A secretive duck with grey/blue plumage flecked with brown on the back. The bill is pale pink. Hymenolaimus malacorhynchus.
Whakamārama: He otaota hāwere, kei runga i ngā rākau o te ngahere e tupu ana. He whiri te āhua, tautau iho ai.
Scope Note: A type of club-moss living as an epiphyte. The drooping fertile stems are like square whiri/plaits branched into two. Lycopodium billardieri.
Whakamārama: Ko te wiki kotahi i wehea ia tau hei whakanui i te reo Māori a-tuhi, a-waha.
Scope Note: A week featuring special emphasis on the use of written and spoken Māori, held once a year.
Whakamārama: He otaota rārāpiri pērā i te peka ā waka. He tokomanga, he kōwhaitea ngā tātā. Ko ngā pua he mā, he kura a waenganui.
Scope Note: An epiphytic orchid with branched yellowish stems and white flowers with reddish-purple centres. Dendrobium cunninghamii.
Scope Note: Quivering of the hands demonstrates the heat waves from Tāne-Rore and his wives Hine-Raumati and Hine-Takurua.
Whakamārama: He tarutaru rite ki te pūrekireki, tupu ai i ngā wāhi reporepo.
Scope Note: A term for small rushes resembling sedges, forming mats in wet places. Juncus spp.
